<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 16:00 GMT, March 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The United Nations monitoring groups and inspection
teams carried out their mission in Iraq smoothly on Sunday, the
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted sources at the Iraqi National Monitoring
Directorate as saying that nine monitoring groups visited on
Sunday 12 sites and helicopters were used to reach a number of
these sites while one helicopter's mission was canceled due to bad
weather conditions. The sources said these visits had received
full cooperation from the Iraqi side. (Iraq-U.N.-Arms Inspections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- U.S President Bill Clinton on Sunday left for
Botswana, concluding his four-day state visit to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his wife Hillary were seen off by South African
Minister for Public Works Jeff Radebe, who is acting Foreign
Affairs Minister. (S. Africa-departure)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Naval forces of Kuwait and the United States on
Sunday held a one-day military exercise in the Kuwaiti waters, the
Kuwaiti News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The war-game was aimed at upgrading the capabilities of the
Kuwaiti navy and adding experience to it, a military source was
quoted by the news agency as saying. (Kuwait-U.S.-Wargame)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- After two rounds of talks with Israeli and
Palestinian leaders, the United States Middle East Peace
Coordinator Dennis Ross will continue his efforts on Sunday to
break the deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat in Gaza city Saturday night, Ross told
reporters that more talks are needed to revive the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, which have been stalled for
months over the extent of next Israeli troop pullback in the West
Bank. (Israel-Ross-Peace Efforts) 
</P>
</TEXT>
