<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Health Workers Seek Co-op </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 29 (Xinhua) -- As Israeli and Palestinian
leaders were holding talks with an American envoy to break the
peace impasse, their health professionals gathered Sunday in Gaza
city to seek ways of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Israel sent a large delegation, mainly staff from the medical
school of Ben-Gurion University, to the meeting while the
Palestinian team was headed by Suha Arafat, wife of President
Yasser Arafat, who is responsible for humanitarian aid in the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides discussed proposals for
launching several joint projects in the field of health.
</P>
<P>
Avishai Brobman, president of Ben-Gurion University, told
Israel Radio that Israel and the PNA are considering establishing
a medical training center in the border region between Gaza and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
As part of a World Health Organization (WHO) program, he
added, the two sides are also going to cooperate in medical
research for health development in border areas.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the medical school of his university will help
the PNA train medical professionals in various fields.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the meaning of this cooperation, Brobman said
that "without support and cooperation in economic and health,
there is no future for coexistence (of Israeli and Palestinian
people)." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
