<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-29 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Politicians Trade Barbs Over U.S. Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli leftist and rightist
politicians Sunday traded accusations over U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's sharp warning over the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Albright told U.S. Jewish leaders in a Friday phone call that
the Israeli-Palestinian peace process is nearing its end and the
U.S. might remove itself from the process if the stalemate
continues.
</P>
<P>
She also expressed doubt about Israeli leaders for their
hostility towards the new U.S. initiative on Israel's further
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The leading opposition Labor Party strongly denounced the
Likud-led ruling coalition for destroying both the peace process
and the strategic relationship with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Labor lawmaker Nissim Zvili called for convening a special
session of the Knesset (Parliament), which is at its spring
recess, to debate the worsening situation of the peace process and
the full-blown crisis with Washington.
</P>
<P>
Another Labor lawmaker Dalia Itzik charged the Likud government
of eroding the crucial relations with the U.S., saying Israel is
losing its "last friend."
</P>
<P>
But the rightist defended Israel's firm stand over the peace
process, especially on the issue of security. Likud's leading
hardliner Zeev Begin said he and some other rightist lawmakers
would topple the government if it bows to U.S. pressure to hand
over more land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Likud's National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon told a
weekly Cabinet session Sunday that he would not agree to accept a
redeployment of more than 9 percent in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The coalition party National Religious Party criticized the
government for considering to a more than 9 percent withdrawal,
saying this would lay the groundwork for an independent
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Likud's faction leader in the Knesset Meir Shetrit denounced
the Labor for automatically siding with the Palestinians. He also
criticized the rightist hardliners for issuing threats over the
government's handling of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is still committed to finding a final
settlement with the Palestinian side if it keeps its commitments
to fight terror to ensure Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu reiterated his position in
Sunday's Cabinet session that there must be clear connection
between Israel's carrying out of further pullouts in the West Bank
and the Palestinian fight against terror.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told the Cabinet that he and visiting U.S. peace
envoy Dennis Ross had not yet discussed the exact percentage of
redeployment during two rounds of talks in the past two days. The
two focused on the so-called "reciprocity," the principle Israel
demands for continuing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Ross were to meet for the third time late Sunday
to get down to the very issue of fixing the percentage of further
redeployment. The U.S. is proposing a 13.1 percent Israeli
pullout, but Israel has said it would not accept anything more
than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Following the Cabinet meeting, Israel's Public Security
Minister Avigdor Kahalani traveled to Gaza to meet with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani said they mainly discussed the security issue rather
than the further redeployment. He disclosed that Arafat was
worried about the prolonged deadlock in the peace process,
although the Palestinian leader has not given up his hope.
</P>
<P>
Also on Sunday, Arafat dispatched Planning and International
Cooperation Minister Nabil Sha'ath to Egypt and chief negotiator
Saeb Erekat to Jordan to brief the two countries' leaders on the
outcome of his two meetings with Ross and the Palestinian stand
over Israeli redeployments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
