<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Leader Adams Urges End to Attacks in Ulster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Gerry Adams, leader of the Irish
Republican Army's (IRA) political wing Sinn Fein, Sunday called
for an immediate end to attacks in Northern Ireland amid the
latest eruption of violence.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Irish National Liberation Army (INLA),
a splinter group of the IRA, shot dead a former police officer
Cyril Stewart in Northern Ireland last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the violence of the INLA guerillas, Adams was
reported as saying in Belfast: "I have said some long time ago
that that organization (INLA) should disband. It has on a number
of occasions brought the entire struggle here into disrepute."
</P>
<P>
He also called on all conflicting sides in Northern Ireland to
exercise restraint and concentrate on the all-party peace talks on
the future of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"It should not deflect anyone from the challenge of bringing
about proper, meaningful, substantive, transitional change in this
situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish
counterpart Bertie Ahern had reportedly exchanged views by
telephone on the serious situation in Northern Ireland over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The London and Dublin governments have promised to stage
referendums in British ruled-Northern Ireland in a bid to resolve
the long-standing dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
