<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Warring Sides Urged to Honor Promises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the U.N. Sanction
Commission Njuguma Mahugu said here Sunday U.N. Security council
will not allow the two warring sides to reset timetable for the
implementation of the 1994 Lusaka Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
Mahugu, who has just finished his week-long visit to Angola,
said the Security Council hopes that both sides keep their
promises made on March 6 to complete the peace process by March
31.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official has come here to show how the Security
Council is worried over the delay of the Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
He called on the two sides to follow the new timetable the
Joint Commission for peace process set on March 6 of completing
the implementation of the process by March 31 without any delay
because he said the Security Council will not accept another
timetable.
</P>
<P>
Mahugu said that he met with Angolan President Jose Eduardo
Dos Santos and other government leaders and also held talks with
the leader of the opposition National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has devoted itself fully to the peace
process and is willing to seek political solution to the problems
facing the nation, Mahugu said, adding that UNITA also expressed
its willingness to commit itself to the process until peace is
ultimately achieved.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official said that there appeared fine signs for the
peace process, adding that he was satisfied with the attitudes of
the warring sides toward implementing the jointly-designated
process.
</P>
<P>
Mahugu also disclosed that he will visit Democratic Congo,
Zambia, Namibia, Togo and Cote d'Ivoire, convey letters from the
Security Council to leaders of these states.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council believes that at the critical
moment, it's necessary to mobilize all sides to make sure that
the Lusaka Peace Accord be implemented and hopes that the leaders
of the region will make diplomatic efforts to urge the two
warring sides in Angola to honor their promises and successfully
complete the peace process, said Mahugu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
