<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Continues in East S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Fighting is continuing in eastern
Sierra Leone as the west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG)
encounters pockets of resistance from remnants of the ousted
military junta.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ECOMOG's pro-government ally of hunters militiamen
known as the Kamajors is gaining grounds in Kalohon and
neighboring districts in the eastern border area with Liberia,
the British Broadcasting Corporation reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors have reportedly taken over such key towns as
Bunumbu, Miama and Mobi in the area, with thousands of the junta
forces and its rebel ally Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
holding others.
</P>
<P>
In an important step to mop up the junta forces and RUF
rebels, ECOMOG last weekend recaptured Dairo barracks and the
town itself which served for more than six weeks as the base of
the junta forces and RUF rebels in the east of the war-ravaged
country.
</P>
<P>
The recapture of Dairo barracks, according to a Kamajor
commander, resulted in the surrender of hundreds of the junta
soldiers and removed the major resistance ECOMOG and the Kamajors
may have met with.
</P>
<P>
But many junta soldiers had fled after being defeated, the
commander said, expressing fear that the fleeing of junta
soldiers would lead to the killing of civilians in places where
they reach.
</P>
<P>
However, an ECOMOG field commander said confidently that the
remnants of junta forces and RUF rebels could be cleaned up in
the next several weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
