<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-29 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Chief Calls for Oil Output Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 29 (Xinhua) -- President of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) Obeid bin Saif Al Nasir
Sunday urged non-OPEC oil producers to help shore up oil prices by
cutting oil output.
</P>
<P>
Obeid, who is also Minister of Petroleum and Mineral Resources
of the United Arab Emirates (UAE), told the official Wam News
Agency before leaving for Monday's emergency ministerial OPEC
meeting in Vienna that non-OPEC oil producers should cooperate
with the bloc to rescue declined oil markets.
</P>
<P>
In this field, he said, these countries should follow the
sample of non-OPEC Mexico, which orchestrated with Saudi Arabia and
Venezuela a deal in Riyadh last Monday to trim oil production by
up to 2 million barrels per day (bpd) from the beginning of April
to the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The deal was expected to be discussed during the Vienna meeting
to be attended by OPEC oil ministers and officials from some of
non-OPEC countries, the OPEC chief said.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen oil producing countries have so far agreed to cut
output by 1.1 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
If the Riyadh accord can be implemented, it will be the first
time that world oil producers have managed to agree to lower
output with the aim of propping up oil prices.
</P>
<P>
World oil prices had gained legs up by nearly 14 percent to
over 15 U.S. dollars a barrel earlier this week. But the prices
fell back when traders paused for breath to wait for the
implementation of the pact.
</P>
<P>
Prices began to collapse after OPEC decided in November to
raise its combined output ceiling by 10 percent to reach 27.5
million bpd.
</P>
<P>
The price crisis was compounded by Iraq's return to oil
markets and a decline in crude demand due to a mild winter in the
northern hemisphere and Asia's economic turmoil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0015 </DOCNO>
