<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-29 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran-Norway Ties Might Worsen over Rushdie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran warned on Sunday it's ties
with Norway might further worsen if Oslo continues support for
Salman Rushdie, a British writer condemned to death by Iran for
his "blasphemous" novel.
</P>
<P>
"The continuation of the offensive policies by Norway might
force Iran to further limit its ties with the country," Foreign
Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said, quoted by the official
Islamic Republic News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Rushdie was condemned to death in 1989 by Iran's late Spiritual
Leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomenei for his novel "the Satanic
Verses," which was regarded as an insult to the Islamic Prophet
Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to a recent meeting between Norwegian Prime Minister
Kjell Magne Bondevik and Rushdie, Mohammadi said "the meeting
constituted a support for Rushdie's desecration of Islamic
sanctities."
</P>
<P>
He said Norway's move defied the new international consensus
which views understanding among nations and dialogue among
cultures and civilizations necessary for peaceful coexistence in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Norway recalled their ambassadors in December 1994
over Norway's support for Rushdie and their ties have since been
kept at the level of charge d'affaires.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said the restrictions Iran imposed on its commercial
and political relations with Norway would continue "unabatedly."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: U.S. Peace Proposals Should Be Balanced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said here Sunday that the latest U.S. peace proposals
should balance the Palestinian and Israeli interests in order to
implement their signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt sees the importance of striking a balance in commitments
of both sides in order to help the signed agreements work," Moussa
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said U.S. Mideast Peace Coordinator Dennis Ross will hold
talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in the Red Sea resort
of Sharm el-Sheikh Monday to expound the American proposals on
revitalizing the peace process as well as the Palestinian and
Israeli reactions towards them.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, carried by Ross on his current shuttle meetings
with the Israeli and Palestinian leaders, suggests that the
Israeli troops pull back from 13.1 percent of the West Bank in 12
weeks in accordance with Palestinians' crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Any proposed ideas should supposedly go in line with the
agreed-upon principles in Madrid Peace Conference in 1991," he
said, adding that the second phase of Israeli redeployment, as
proposed in the U.S. initiative, should be followed by a third one.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that he and Egyptian Presidential Political Advisor
Osama el-Baz will meet Sunday night with a Palestinian delegation
headed by Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil
Shaath to listen to their assessment of the latest contacts.
</P>
<P>
After Ross' rounds of talks with the Palestinians and the
Israelis, the Palestinians announced Sunday that they tended to
accept the U.S. proposals while Israeli leaders insisted that the
13.1 percent proposed by the Americans is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
After the U.S. envoy leaves the region, Arafat is expected to
visit Cairo to have consultations with the Egyptian leadership
before drawing up a final Palestinian stance regarding the
U.S. initiative, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During the past three days, Ross paid visits to Israel and the
Palestinian self-rule areas in a bid to revive Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks, which have been stalled for months over the extent of
next Israeli troops pullback from the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
