<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu, Ross Discuss Israeli Pullout Scope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu held a third meeting with visiting U.S. peace envoy
Dennis Ross to discuss the scope of Israeli further redeployment
in the West Bank Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
The two held talks at the Prime Minister's Office for over two
hours, but no details were disclosed about the content of their
discussion. Neither of them spoke to reporters before and after
the meeting, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Ross traveled to Gaza after the meeting to hold a third round
of talks with Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat to brief him on the latest Israeli position.
</P>
<P>
The two sides began focusing their talks on solving a dispute
over the scope of Israel's second of the three-phased troops
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Sunday morning's weekly Cabinet session, Netanyahu
said his past two meetings with Ross only dealt with the
conditions Israel had set for continuing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel is insisting on the so-called principle of
"reciprocity," which means the PNA should honor its commitments
to fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
No quick breakthrough was expected from Ross' current mission
on settling the issue of further redeployment. The U.S. is
proposing for a 13.1 percent Israeli pullout from the West Bank,
but Israel has said it would not accept anything more than 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
At the Cabinet meeting, influential National Infrastructure
Minister Ariel Sharon warned the government against accepting a
pullout of more than 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani, who met with Arafat
in Gaza Sunday, said he supported only a pullout of no more than
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Also on Sunday, Arafat dispatched Planning and International
Cooperation Minister Nabil Sha'ath to Cairo and chief negotiator
Saeb Erekat to Jordan to brief the two countries' leaders on the
outcome of his two meetings with Ross and the Palestinian stand
over Israeli redeployments.
</P>
<P>
Ross is to travel to Egypt Monday to discuss with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak the Israeli further redeployment and to
win the latter's support to lower the PNA's expectation.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has previously insisted that Israel should carry out
at least 30 percent pullout in the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Another round of talks between Ross and Israeli and Palestinian
leaders are expected following his return from Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
