<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Praises Botswana, Masire Welcomes U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
praised Botswana as the oldest democracy in Africa while Botswana
President Ketumile Masire commended Washington's Africa trade
initiative, a report from Gaborone reaching here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen the promise of a new Africa whose roots are deep
here in your soil, for you have been an inspiration to all those
who cherish freedom," the Botswana Press Association (BOPA)
quoted Clinton as saying.
</P>
<P>
At a reception in his honor at the State House Sunday in
Gaborone, Clinton told outgoing President Ketumile Masire and
president-designate Festus Mogae that "America is determined to
support all those who follow your lead."
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. and Botswana would build on the spirit of
cooperation to renew their partnership for the future.
</P>
<P>
Clinton paid tribute to Masire for his economic leadership of
Botswana and the peaceful hand-over, in two days' time, of power
to Mogae.
</P>
<P>
"First as vice-president and minister of finance, you sparked
the engine of an economic miracle."
</P>
<P>
He announced that the U.S. would establish a division of Voice
of America on the continent, Radio Democracy for Africa.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Masire expressed support for Washington's Africa
trade initiative, referring to the U.S.-Africa Growth and
Opportunity Bill as "America's solemn bond to Africa."
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate your support for the African Growth and
Opportunity Bill which was passed by the House of Representatives
recently," Masire said.
</P>
<P>
"This act will facilitate the industrialization of our
economies and the transfer of essential technology.
</P>
<P>
"I and my government applaud the objective of creating the
opportunity for African countries to become participants in the
global economy by accessing the world's largest market."
</P>
<P>
In regard to the U.S. legislation, Masire's viewpoint was in
sharp contrast to that of South African leaders, who believed
that the bill was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. bill is aimed at replacing aid with trade, opening
African market and at the same ihgD6ow access to African goods
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Clinton left Gaborone for the northern town of Kasane, where
he and his wife Hillary would spent Cm of a
retreat. The Clintons are scheduled to fly back to Gaborone
Tuesday in their way to Senegal, the last leg of their six-nation
African tour. The couple have visited Ghana, Uganda, Rwanda and
South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
