<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Albanian Defense Ministers Discuss Balkan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos discussed Sunday with his visiting Albanian
counterpart, Sabit Brokaj, the establishment of a multinational
peacekeeping force in the Balkan region, the situation in the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo and the recent upsurge in crime in
Greece.
</P>
<P>
During their talks which took place in the northwestern Greek
town of Ioannina, the two ministers agreed that the Balkan Defense
Undersecretaries meet again in the Albanian capital of Tirana on
May 21, the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Greece is currently promoting the idea of a multinational
Balkan force, first put forward last October, with the aim of
preventing regional crisis from escalating into armed conflict and
carrying out humanitarian missions.
</P>
<P>
The Greek proposal was discussed in Sofia, Bulgaria, last
October at a meeting of Balkan Defense Undersecretaries.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos said after their talks that Greece opposed armed
violence in Kosovo while it endorsed respect of human rights. The
settlement of the Kosovo problem could be achieved only through
dialogue between the parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that his country had never been, nor would
ever become, a racist country.
</P>
<P>
Brokaj said that some isolated incidents did not affect the
good relations between Albania and Greece.
</P>
<P>
They were referring to the recent wave of violent crimes
committed throughout Greece which has blamed some foreigners,
especially illegal Albanian immigrants for the crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
