<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Oil Price Inches up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Oil prices of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) rose dramatically on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The price of OPEC's basket of seven crudes climbed to 13.20
U.S. dollars a barrel from 11.22 dollars a week ago, the
secretariat of the leading international oil group said.
</P>
<P>
The rise resulted from the decision by Saudi Arabia, OPEC's
leading member, and other OPEC members together with some non-OPEC
oil producers, to reduce daily oil production beginning on April 1.
</P>
<P>
An OPEC meeting, which is due to be held late Monday here, is
believed to contribute to the increase. The meeting will focus
on production cuts aimed at boosting oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The price of OPEC's basket of seven crudes fell to 10.91
dollars a barrel on March 16 and oil markets were adrift at
nine-year lows on the next day as producers failed to curb
swelling supply.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil exporter, is locked in a
dispute with Venezuela, OPEC's biggest over-producer, over
responsibility for the price fall.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC groups Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya,
Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and the United Arab
Emirates. It is estimated that the OPEC members possess 75 percent
of the world's known reserves of crude oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Trade Minister on Protecting Investment In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Canada's International Trade
Minister Sergio Marchi, who is making an official visit to China,
spoke today about the prospects of agreements protecting Canadian
and Chinese investment.
</P>
<P>
Marchi said that agreements on safeguarding investment would
provide the right framework for the two countries' enterprises and
give them the confidence they are seeking.
</P>
<P>
Canada has invested more than 1.5 billion U.S. dollars in
China, and Chinese businesses have begun to invest in Canada. And,
although China has similar agreements with more than 70 countries,
it and Canada have yet to reach an agreement to protect their
investment.
</P>
<P>
Marchi attributes this to the fact that both nations have
signed agreements with other countries and have different
standards. However, he said he believes that because the
agreements reflect the common interests and trust of businesses,
an agreement can be reached within months.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chinese officials will further discuss the issue
when they visit Ottawa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
