<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Rules out Third Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
reiterated Monday that he would not run for the presidential
elections in the year 2000, but he did not name sacked Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin as his successor.
</P>
<P>
"We don't have a tradition of successors," an Itar-Tass report
quoted Yeltsin as saying. "It is the kings who are successors."
</P>
<P>
"In our country people elect leaders, and every citizen has the
right to run for presidency under the constitution," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, Chernomyrdin's Saturday declaration on
presidential bid in 2000 "is in keeping with the president's
thoughts."
</P>
<P>
"I made the decision on the cabinet's dismissal, having in mind
at the same time that he would lead the presidential campaign of
the year 2000," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday last week, Yeltsin suddenly fired Chernomyrdin and
his entire government, saying that they had "failed to cope with a
number of social problems."
</P>
<P>
In a TV address following his surprise order of dismissal,
Yeltsin stressed that the year 2000 elections are of enormous
importance to Russia, so he had instructed Chernomyrdin to
concentrate on political preparations for these elections.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, who has served for more than five years in the
post of prime minister, announced over the weekend that he would
definitely be a candidate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
