<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Conducts Consultancy Study on Sustainable Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government
announced here Monday that it has commissioned a consultancy study
on the sustainable development for Hong Kong in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Announcing details of the Study on Sustainable Development for
the 21st Century (SUSDEV21) at a press conference, Peter Pun,
director of planning of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region, said that the aim of the study is to develop a framework
to help government make decisions for Hong Kong's future in a
balanced and sustainable way.
</P>
<P>
The SUSDEV 21 study began in September 1997 and will be
completed by the end of the next year.
</P>
<P>
Upon the completion of the study, a decision-making framework
will be worked out for sustainable development in Hong Kong which
aims to balance the economic, social and environmental needs of
the community, Pun said.
</P>
<P>
In another word, the SUSDEV21 will help government ensure that
all relevant environmental, social and economic aspects of
development proposals are well coordinated and balanced.
</P>
<P>
Pun said that the task for the government at present is to let
people know what the SUSDEV21 is.
</P>
<P>
The SUSDEV21 does not tackle any specific issues such as the
environment, the economic development and housing. In stead, it
takes all factors into consideration and will work out a system to
help the government make its policies concerning Hong Kong's
long-term development in the future, Pun said.
</P>
<P>
"If Hong Kong is to continue to thrive in the next century, we
need to maintain our environmental quality at an acceptable level
and safeguard the integrity of our natural resource base and
cultural heritage while at the same time continuing to meet
development pressure arising from growing social and economic
needs," Pun said.
</P>
<P>
"Our study will develop guiding values, sustainability
indicators and criteria covering the economic, social and
environmental aspects to provide a basis for measuring our
performance on sustainability," he added.
</P>
<P>
While the study was mainly confined to Hong Kong, the
consultants had to examine developments in the wider Pearl River
Delta Region in Southern China, particularly in respect of
socio-economic and infrastructure developments and cross-boundary
environmental issues, Pun said.
</P>
<P>
A fundamental principle of sustainable development is that
activities arising from decisions taken today should not
compromise the quality of life or economic well-being of the
future.
</P>
<P>
The government's intention to embrace sustainable development
is driven by a commitment to enable Hong Kong to continue to
prosper and allow the economic, social and environmental
aspirations of the people of Hong Kong to be fulfilled. It cannot
succeed without the support and participation of the community.
</P>
<P>
Views of the community will be collected at various stages to
help ensure that appropriate values and indicators are built into
the new decision-making system to form the basis for adjustments,
if necessary, in inter-related policies, plans and programs, Pun
said.
</P>
<P>
"To achieve this, we will launch an extensive public awareness
and consultation program on April 2 to enhance the community's
understanding of the issue," Pun said. The program will last for
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
