<HEADLINE> Chinese Ass't Minister Says Cross-Straits Ties Need Guarding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- An Min, China's Assistant
Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, speaking today
at the opening of a two-day symposium on international trade laws,
said that the current sound cross-Straits economic and trade
relations that have taken shape over the past two decades need to
be safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
The symposium is being sponsored by law schools at the
mainland's University of International Business and Economics
and at Taiwan's Soochow University.
</P>
<P>
An quoted statistics from the central government on the
cross-straits trade, showing that by the end of 1997, it was worth
116.4 billion US dollars, with the mainland suffering a deficit of
80 billion US dollars. The mainland also had 18.4 billion US
dollars worth of investment from Taiwan, and in 1997 alone,
cross-Straits trade stood at 19.84 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan is the mainland's fifth largest trade partner and the
mainland and Hong Kong have become Taiwan's second largest market,
third largest trade partner, and the third investment spot.
</P>
<P>
The two benefit each other in the economy and the mainland will
further open up by depending even more on Taiwanese funds,
technology, and markets, while Taiwan needs new markets to improve
the viability of its products and boost its technology, An said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that commercial and industrial sectors
will help to remove barriers and develop cross-Strait's trade for
the economic prosperity of both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
