<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Becoming Modern Farmers Because of Institutional Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, March 30 (Xinhua) -- It's no more shuffling papers
and no more boring meetings for Yang Zhigang, who used to work in
a county magistrate's office in east China's Jiangxi Province,
just life in the countryside and the joy of farming.
</P>
<P>
This new life Yang chose for himself began several months ago
when he resigned his position as deputy magistrate of Wuning
County and started working 33 hectares of barren hillside and 5.3
hectares of water under contract.
</P>
<P>
The 43-year-old Yang explains his decision by saying,
"Government institutions are overstaffed, and I just don't want to
stay idle every day," so he's at the head of a group of farmers,
planting fruit trees and herbal medicines and starting to breed
pigs, chicken, ducks and fish. He is also planning to set up
places to process his farm products.
</P>
<P>
Yang's move represents a new trend among some government
employees. The new Chinese cabinet that was formed earlier this
month has announced a bold reform plan that requires both the
central and local governments to cut the number of employees in
half by combining redundant departments.
</P>
<P>
Each year China spends nearly half its revenues on the salaries
of more than 30 million officials whose work is often redundant,
bureaucratic, and terribly inefficient, and some employees are
increasingly aware of the inevitability of major institutional
reforms.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, some redundant employees will be
transferred to industrial and commercial administration, or tax
and supervisory departments, while others will just have to find
new jobs in various other sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
