<HEADLINE> Officials Become Modern Farmers Because of Institutional Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Wuning, approximately 200 kilometers from Nanchang,
Jiangxi's capital, nearly a fifth of the county government
officials have resigned their posts and got involved in
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
One former official with the Organization Department of the
Wuning County Communist Party Committee, Ye Zhijun, said they
should play a leading role in commercialization and specialization
in agriculture. The 37-year-old Ye has a contract on 460 hectares
of barren hillsides and 660 hectares of water, and in addition to
planting fruit trees and breeding fish he is contemplating the
possibility of using his farm for tourism.
</P>
<P>
According to the Wuning county magistrate, Wei Hongbin, these
farmer-officials had cultivated thousands of hectares of hillside
and thousands of hectares of unused water space by the end of
1997, and the figures keep growing.
</P>
<P>
The officials are using their own potential and have created
new job opportunities in the countryside with their farms, Wei
said, explaining that they have taught farmers how to improve farm
technology.
</P>
<P>
The Jiangxi provincial government has praised the practice in
Wuning. And it's no wonder, since the director of the provincial
government's Finance Department, Yong Zhongcheng, said that there
are more than a million government-supported officials in Jiangxi
who account for a fortieth of the population, but 60 percent of
the province's annual revenues is spent on their salaries.
</P>
<P>
Reducing the number of officials could not only save the
government money that could be used for developing the economy,
but it could also improve officials' work and the government's
efficiency, Yong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
