<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa to Launch Development Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG March 30 (Xinhua) -- Finance officials from the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) have recommended
the establishment of a fund to support development in the region.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was discussed by senior finance officials at a
meeting of the SADC's finance and investment sector coordinating
unit, led by South Africa's Finance Department, Business Day
paper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The fund would primarily be financed by the governments of the
14-nation bloc although the private sector might be allowed to
make contributions, said Bongi Kunene, director in charge of the
SADC's finance and investment sector.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed the role the World Bank might play
amid changing patterns in developmenp finance. The bank has
signalled a willingness to contribute to such a fund to reduce
political risk.
</P>
<P>
The idea of an SADC development fund, which might be managed
by South Africa's Development Bank of Southern Africa, marks a
radical shift from an earlier notion of an SADC development bank.
</P>
<P>
One of the suggested functions of the fund is to provide
cushioning against revenue loss resulting drom tariff elimination
under the planned SADC's free trade area.
</P>
<P>
The other possibility was for the fund to function along the
lines of the European Union's cohesive program.
</P>
<P>
It was also recommended that SADC countries should work
towards macroeconomic convergence.
</P>
<P>
Kunene said her unit would now draft principles for an SADC
finance and investment protocol, which would be presented to
finance ministers in June for consideration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
