<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's GDP Rises 10.7 percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) in 1996 was estimated at 1,192.4 billion HK dollars
(152.87 billion U.S. dollars) at current market prices,
representing an increase of 10.7 percent over the preceding year.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary figures released by the Census and Statistics
Department here Monday show that taking the size of the population
into consideration, per capita GDP at current market prices
increased by eight percent to 188,933 HK dollars (24,222 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
After discounting price changes, the real Gross National Income
(GNI) recorded an increase of 4.6 percent in 1996, not much below
the five percent growth in GDP at constant prices, when further
adjusted for change in the terms of trade.
</P>
<P>
Total external factor income inflow into Hong Kong was 383.8
billion HK dollars (49.21 billion U.S. dollars), within which
direct investment income (DII) and portfolio investment income
(PII) rose by 12.3 percent and 8.6 percent respectively in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Total factor income outflow grew by 5.4 percent to 393 billion
HK dollars (50.38 billion U.S. dollars), within which DII and PII
gained by 13.3 percent and 19.5 percent respectively in the year.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the latest figures, a Government Secretariat
Spokesman said that Hong Kong is a highly externally oriented
economy with substantial international transaction flows.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting this, he said both the external factor income inflow
and external factor income outflow continued to be sizable in
1996. The overall factor income account was broadly balanced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that both DII inflow and outflow recorded
robust growth in 1996, reflecting good return from both outward
direct investment and inward direct investment to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
PII outflow showed a much faster increase than PII inflow in
1996. This was due to the faster expansion and relatively better
performance of the local stock market as compared to many of the
major stock market overseas, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
