<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Globalization Reduces Macro-economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
Monday said that the globalization of the world economy had
reduced the autonomy of the developing countries in determining
their macro-economic policies.
</P>
<P>
He was opening a Conference on Defending Workers' Human Rights
in the Global Economy sponsored by the African Regional
Organization (AFRO) oF the Intepnational Confederation of Free
Trade Unions (ICFTU).
</P>
<P>
Equally, the president noted, the flexibility of trade unions
to determine and ensure strict application of employment policies
has also been eroded.
</P>
<P>
While acknowledging that the economic globalization had a
positive impact on economic growth of many countries, Moi pointed
out that employment security of workers had been reduced over the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of full time workers with prospects for career
development is falling in relation to that of casual workers, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Moi called for fair compensation for workers as
the short term effects of economic reforms had not been asy on
the welfare of orkers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, ICFTU-ADRO General Secretary
Andrew Kailembo noted that "unless the global market is
re-oriented, economic development will continue to benefit just a
few powerful multi-nationals."
</P>
<P>
The multi-national corporations will increase their trade and
investments in developing countries, but the ordinary people and
the countries in which they operate "will gain close to nothing
in return", he added.
</P>
<P>
J.J. Mugalla, Secretary General of Kenyan Central Organization
of TradeUnions, Monday told the three-day meeting that
"Globalization is producing wealth and riches for the minority
and poverty and insecurity for the majority", adding that "the
gap between the poor and the rich s widening."
</P>
<P>
The meting is aimed at discussing the issue of the "Social
Clause" which has something to do with the use of slave labour,
forced labour and child labour in the production of goods and
services for international trade.
</P>
<P>
According to the meeting, the number of child workers between
5 and 14 years of age in Africa is around 80 million and the
figure will rise with at least onE million new child workers
annually in the next 10 to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also discus, among other things, the African
development challenges with special reference to Structural
Adjustment Programs, and equal opportunity for women and men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
