<HEADLINE> China's Largest City Looking for More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing municipality, southwest
China, will invite the top 500 multinationals to invest and will
grant preferential treatment to foreign investors, its Vice-Mayor
Xu Zhongmin told a press conference today.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has issued a report to some foreign
embassies and big companies in Beijing on this, Xu said, and it
will develop new industries in relation to the Three Gorges
project, and plans to become a modern metropolis by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
This is Chongqing's first high-profile report since becoming
China's fourth municipality direct under the central government in
March last year.
</P>
<P>
The city is now playing a leading role in developing the
economy in central and western parts of China and is welcoming
foreign investment in the automobile, motorcycle, electronic
information, food, medicine, and chemical industries and in
enovating state enterprises, according to Tang Wenfeng, director
of Chongqing Economic Technological Development Zone's management
office.
</P>
<P>
The zone is the only national economic and technological
development zone in western China and that it will be a golden
area for foreign investment, Tang said. More than 40 countries and
regions have set up ventures in Chongqing, which has a population
of 30 million.  
</P>
