-- Interim premier Sergei Kiriyenko said he wants to bring new
faces into Russia's government and will not bargain over cabinet
lists to win parliamentary approval for his nomination as prime
minister. President Boris Yeltsin dismissed prime minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin and his government last Monday, and named Kiriyenko,
35, interim premier, then nominated him Friday for the permanent
job.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- A Senate panel unveiled only parts of a much-anticipated
tobacco bill, avoiding the question of legal relief for the
industry. Committee negotiators had reached a tentative agreement
on the legal protections, but, facing almost certain opposition,
chose against disclosing it.
</P>
<P>
-- Oil producers will meet in Vienna to clarify ambiguities in
the agreement OPEC is expected to ratify early this week. The way
the details are resolved could affect the size of the production
cuts. The agreement, hashed out more than a week ago by Saudi
Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico, will produce at least 1.5 billion
barrels a day of cuts from current worldwide production
levels. 
