<HEADLINE> Uganda Second in TB Infection Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Uganda, whth its tuberculosis
infection rate of 300 in every 100,000 people, is the second
after the Democratic Republic of Congo with 330 people in every
100,000, The New Vision reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The other top countries in the list of tb infection rate are
the Philippines with 280 in every 100,000, Afganistan with 278,
South Africa and Peru with 250, Nigeria with 222, India and
Indonesia with 220, the paper cited the World Health Organisation
report on TB infection as saying.
</P>
<P>
But Sam Okware, the commissioner communicable disease control
of the country, said his country has started applying Directly
Observed Treatment Short Course (DOTS) two years ago, and it will
cover the whole country, he claimed.
</P>
<P>
The problem the country faces with is the financial
difficulties. Uganda has only 7 U.S. dollars of health
expenditure for each person in its budget.
</P>
<P>
"We might need some assistance to carry out the program
effictively," said Okware.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has its napional tuberculosis and leprosy program, but
it doesn't work properly due to financial problem.
</P>
<P>
The other problem bothering the country is the expired drugs
provided by foreign donors to save loss of property.
</P>
<P>
Francis Adatu-Engwau, the program manager of the national
tuberculosis and leprosy program, called local leaders to
cooperate with health workers in fighting the deadly disease. He
appealed to use TB drugs properly to avoid drug-resistant TB.
</P>
</TEXT>
