<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Meets With U.S. Mideast Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
held talks on Monday with the United States Mideast envoy Dennis
Ross on ways of breaking deadlock in the Mideast peace process,
the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
They reviewed the latest situations in the region in the light
of Ross' talks with Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Since last Thursday, Ross has been shuttling between Arafat and
Netanyahu in a bid to win their acceptance of a U.S. plan calling
on Israel to withdraw from 13.1 percent of the West Bank over 12
weeks, linked to Palestinian crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians and Israel are cool to the plan. Israel
has said the withdrawal scope is unacceptable and that it would
pull out from no more than 9 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians insist that Israel carry out three significant
pullbacks by summer this year under U.S.-brokered agreements
signed last year between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, Arafat will travel to Sharm el-Sheikh to
discuss with Mubarak his three rounds of meetings with Ross, the
Al-Akhbar newspaper reported. 
