<P>
She said that China has noticed the new China policy of the
European Commission and will develop a good relationship with the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
Wu also discussed China's state-owned enterprise reforms and
Sino-foreign nuclear energy cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Dondoux, who is here as guest of the Chinese Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, said that France is
satisfied with China's position on the financial crisis in Asia,
and that France hopes to further the bilateral partnership and it
supports China's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Official on Globalization, Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth and higher
consumption levels expected from the globalization process do not
automatically lead to improving people's lives. They are only
the means to achieve equitable and healthy human development,
resident representative of the UNDP Carlos Lopes said Monday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a six-day workshop organized by the
Southern and Eastern African Trade, Information and Negotiations
Initiative (SEATINI) in Harare.
</P>
<P>
He said, since 1980s, the world has experienced rapid
transformations of what is now called a complex global market.
The invisible hands operate globally. The deregulation of
domestic markets and new levels of international competition have
become known universal features.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, the benefits of this new economic trends are
not being distributed evenly across and within borders. Growing
income divergence and increasing inequality in the world's
population has been the rather persistent feature."
</P>
<P>
The rich have become richer while the poor become poorer as
polarization increases at levels never experienced before in
economic history. The richest 20 percent of the world population
gained its income share substantially in the last three decades,
now dominating 83 percent of the world GNP. During the same
period, the ratio of average GNP per capita between the poorest
and richest has doubled, he said.
</P>
<P>
Africa, on the other hand, has failed to reap rewards from the
globalization and liberalization process. The region accounts
for only two percent of the total value of exports, compared to
17 percent in Asia-Pacific (excluding Japan), 48 percent in
Europe, and 15 percent in north America.
</P>
<P>
"The picture is also grim on the human development side in the
region. 40 percent of people in Sub-Saharan Africa are estimated
to be deprived of essential elements of human life such as
longevity, knowledge and decent living standards," the official
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that no country in the world, regardless of its
size, economic or political regime, can avoid facing the
realities of globalization. What each country can do is to
better manage the globalization proess domestically and
internationally.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries must collectively resolve the
international trade regimes that affect their development
process, he said.
</P>
<P>
In order to gain from the globalization and liberalization
process, developing countries must be capacitated with adequate
knowledge and tools. It is only then the states can implement
sound domestic policies and be strategic in their representation
during the international trade negotiation fora, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workshop Opens in Zimbabwe on Regional Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 30 (Xinhua) -- A six-day economic workshop of
the Southern and Eastern African Trade, Information and
Negotiations Initiative (SEATINI) started Monday in Harare.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, attended by more than 100 scholars,
administrators, international negotiators, donors and
practitioners from many parts of the world, will analyse the new
trading regime under the World Trade Organization (WTO) and
consider a common framework of action at the WTO meeting in
Geneva in May this year.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Chandrakant Patel from the office of
special coordinator for the least developed countries (LDCS) and
the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD),
said the importance of this workshop arises from the fact that it
brings together participants to resolve a key policy challenge to
countries in Africa, namely how to strengthen their participation
in the trading system through more effective articulation of
their interests and priorities in the multilateral trade
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote address, Zimbabwean Minister of Industry and
Commerce N. Shamuyarira noted that the entire developing world is
entering a phase of very delicate and difficult negotiations with
the developed world in the context of the WTO and the Lome
Convention. Developing countries need more information and hard
facts on which to base their decisions.
</P>
<P>
In preparation for the second ministerial conference of the
WTO to be held from May 18 to 20, the Organisation of African
Unity (OAU) has suggested what it calls a positive agenda of
issues that concern Africa, which include market access,
industrialisation and investments, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to negotiations for a new economic relationship
between the African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) group and the
European Union, Shamuyarira said, "The thrust of the ACP position
is to retain advantages in the key clauses of the Lome Convention
that provide market access on concessionary terms, while
jettisoning those clauses inspired by a past colonial era."
</P>
<P>
"Of great importance to the ACP countries is the
non-reciprocal trading arrangement. They insist that this
arrangement should be retained for a given period while they
adjust, as well as industrialise their economy," the minister
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Supports Lebanese, Syrian Stance on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi said Monday that his country supports Lebanese and
Syrian stance on Israeli proposal to conditionally withdraw from
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
After talks with his Lebanese counterpart Fares Boueiz,
Kharrazi told a news conference that the Israeli offer was actually
a trap aimed at separating Lebanon from the Syrian track in the
peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel has offered to comply with the United Nations Resolution
425 and withdraw from south Lebanon provided negotiated security
arrangements are agreed by the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
These arrangements include the deployment of Lebanese troops in
the areas to be vacated by Israeli forces and the disarmament of
the Iranian-backed Hezbullah (Party of God) and the reintegration
of members of the pro-Israeli militia, the South Lebanese
Army (SLA), into the Lebanese army.
</P>
<P>
The offer was vehemently rejected by Lebanon and Syria, who
argued that the U.N. resolution 425 calls on Israel to leave
Lebanon without any conditions.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was adopted by the U.N. in 1978 following Israeli
first invasion of Lebanon. It calls for an unconditional Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister also warned that Israel was likely
to launch new heavy assaults on south Lebanon in a bid to press
the Lebanese government to accept its demands.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the Beirut International Airport Monday
morning, Kharrazi said that Lebanon has been in the front line of
the battle against the "Jewish enemy." He expressed concern about
the continuous Israeli attack on south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer "security zone"
in south Lebanon in 1985 with the declaimed aim of protecting its
northern areas from Lebanese guerrillas cross-border attack,
military confrontations between Israeli occupying forces and
Lebanese resistance fighters take place almost everyday.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi arrived here from Syria for a three-day visit. He is
expected to hold talks with Lebanese President Elias Hrawi, House
Speaker Nabih Berry, Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and other
officials on regional developments and bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
He will also deliver a letter from Iranian President Mohammed
Khatami to Hrawi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Publishes Silk Book On Early Military Texts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Textiles Publishing
House has published silk books on China's earliest military works
from the National Museum of Chinese History and the Palace Museum
collections.
</P>
<P>
"Master Sun's Art of War" was woven by a silk company in
Hangzhou in Zhejiang province.
</P>
<P>
The text, preface, and illustrations of the two-volume book are
on 75 satin pages.
</P>
<P>
"Master Sun's Art of War" is China's earliest-known and most
famous military work. Written by Sun Wu in the Spring and Autumn
period (771-476 BC), the book has been translated into 32
languages and has been studied by politicians, economists,
entrepreneurs, and students of military science. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Asks for Foreign Help in Extinguishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos Monday asked
Defense Secretary Fortunato Abat to get foreign assistance to
contain forest fires in Palawan in southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
In a handwritten directive, Ramos also ordered Abat, who is
also the chairman of the National Disaster Coordinating Council,
to step up rain-making efforts to prevent forest fires from
spreading to other provinces of the country.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the President, Palawan Governor Salvador
Socrates said that as of March 29, 27 forest fires were scattered
all over the region, damaging some 15,000 hectares of forest and
54 houses.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has formed two task forces to
extinguish the fires. Philippine Air Force planes also conducted
clouds-seeding in the entire region.
</P>
<P>
Scorates said food and medicines had been sent to areas
affected by the fires. 
</P>
