<HEADLINE> Ramos Sees Productive Results of ASEM in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said here on Monday that he was "most optimistic of productive
results" of the Second Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) to be held in
London.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to British Prime Minister Tony Blair, Ramos said
that unavoidable commitments in the country prevented him from
joining the ASEM, but he has designated Senate President Neptali
Gonzales and Foreign Affairs Secretary Domingo Siazon as his
representatives.
</P>
<P>
The president said he looks to "the adoption of major
initiatives, notably the Asia-Europe Cooperation Framework, as
well as the action plans on investment promotion and on trade
facilitation."
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the second ASEM takes on added significance at it
will be held in the midst of a currency and financial crisis
gripping East and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Both our regions certainly will benefit from a concerted
response to this crisis, particularly cooperation on its early
resolution and more significantly, on the restoration of economic
dynamism in the Asian region," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Ramos also thanked Blair for informing him of
the arrangements being made for the meeting. 
</P>
