<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors want to buy Indonesian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors from the United
States and Europe have expressed interest in buying the Indonesian
government's stakes in five publicly-listed state-owned
enterprises, a senior official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The government warmly welcomes their interest, but has yet to
decide on this, Finance Minister Fuad Bawazier said after meeting
with President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the foreign investors' interest in owning the
government's shares in the state enterprises reflects their
confidence that Indonesia would be able to weather its economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"If they don't see any good prospects (in Indonesia), they
would not make any offer to buy the shares," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that once this is realized, confidence in the
Indonesian economy will easily be restored.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian economy has been burdened by the detrimental
impacts of the sharp plunge in the rupiah (national currency)
since July last year. The rupiah has lost more than 70 percent of
its value against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
This has caused most state-owned and private companies to
become technical bankrupt as their foreign debts surpass their
equity. Many foreign banks have refused to accept their credit
letters (C/Ls) for imports.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has a total of 164 state firms, 70 percent of which
were considered to be financially unhealthy as of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
