<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Vow to Donate Organs After Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- While most Chinese still take the
traditional view that the remains of deceased persons should not
be dissected, some 600 residents in Nanjing have chosen to donate
their organs for medical use after their deaths.
</P>
<P>
They have joined an organ donation group, China's first, which
was founded in Nanjing in February. Among the committed donors,
the oldest is 93 while the youngest is 18.
</P>
<P>
"I am happy to find that more people will donate their organs,"
said the group's initiator, Huang Fuyin, who has received many
inquiries from 27 provinces, cities and autonomous regions,
expressing a willingness to join the move.
</P>
<P>
In Wujing, a city in east China's Jiangsu Province, three
retired teachers in their 80s urged the city to set up a similar
organization dealing with local organ donations. "We hope organ
donations could save more lives in the future," they said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Yi, a retired engineer in his 70s, traveled a long way to
Beijing from Wuhan, central China's Hubei Province, to sign papers
on cornea donations with the Eye Bank of the Tongren Hospital.
</P>
<P>
The result of a Beijing survey shows that, of the 500
respondents, 48.6 percent expressed a willingness to donate their
corneas, contrasting sharply with only 15 people whose answers
were "no."
</P>
<P>
A report from a Nanjing university also revealed 34 percent of
surveyed students said they plan to donate their bodies.
</P>
<P>
Experts describe organic exhaustion as one of the most serious
threats to people's health and life, and acknowledged that organ
transplants have become a popular means of resuing human life in
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
However, China is short of organs for transplant. State sources
said only 2,000 people get organs for transplant each year,
contrasting sharply with 100,000 patients suffering organic
exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
"The move now is gaining more attention than before, thanks to
more powerful publicity by newspapers, TV and radio," said
Huang. The cities of Nanjing and Xi'an have opened centers
responsible for organ donations. Volunteers in Xuzhou have been
awarded commemorative medals thanking them for their kindness.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Nanjing also said that the legal framework for
organ donations is being prepared and urged people to become more
aware of organ donations to save lives.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
