<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BMW Wins Contest for Rolls-Royce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The British engineering group
Vickers PLC has agreed to sell the luxury car-maker Rolls-Royce to
BMW AG of Germany for 340 million pounds (572 million U.S.
dollars), BMW confirmed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the decision by Vickers, a BMW spokesman said in
Munich: "We are honored and also obligated to meet the
expectations of our British partner."
</P>
<P>
While confirming the 340 million pound price tag, the spokesman
said the company would detail its plan about Rolls-Royce at a press
conference on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Vickers, which says it wants to concentrate on its defense
business, put Rolls-Royce up for sale last October, provoking a
fierce contest between BMW and Germany's largest car-maker
Volkswagen AG.
</P>
<P>
Vickers chairman Colin Chandler announced Monday that after
carefully considering a number of proposals, the company found that
BMW's offer was the most attractive one in terms of achieving best
value for shareholders and ensuring the continued success of
Rolls-Royce, the last British-owned car company.
</P>
<P>
BMW, which supplies engines for Silver Seraph, the latest model
of Rolls-Royce, had threatened to withhold supplies if a rival
company won the bidding.
</P>
<P>
The Germany car-maker is expected to invest heavily in
Rolls-Royce over the next 10 years to increase the sales of the
luxury car. Vickers rolled out 1,918 Rolls-Royce last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
