<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Train Ghanaian Soldiers Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States is to begin
training of Ghanaian soldiers next Wednesday, according to the
United States Information Service (USIS) here.
</P>
<P>
A statement, issued by USIS at the weekend, said about 70
soldiers from the U.S. army, accompanied by a Belgian military
training element along with support troops may be deployed
Wednesday "to begin training a battalion size unit in Ghana".
</P>
<P>
The decision of the U.S. Defense Department was announced at
the weekend, barely five days after U.S. President Bill Clinton
arrived in Ghana to begin his six-nation African tour.
</P>
<P>
The effort is aimed at increasing Ghana's peacekeeping skills
as part of the U.S. African Crisis Response Initiative (ACRI),
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said since July last year, when the 3rd Special Forces
Group of the U.S. army started operations, forces in Senegal,
Uganda and Malawi have been trained, while Mali is undergoing its
own training.
</P>
<P>
The ACRI program also entails "follow-on sustainment training
twice a year after the completion of the initial training," the
statement said, citing Senegal and Uganda as beneficiaries of the
sustainment training which started this month.
</P>
<P>
The need to create "highly effective rapidly deployable
peacekeeping units that can operate jointly in the event of a
humanitarian crisis or in a traditional peacekeeping operation"
requires the setting up of the ACRI, which USIS described as a
bilateral training initiative intended to work with the African
states.
</P>
<P>
ACRI is also conducted in tandem with African partners, the
Organization of African Unity and the United Nations, while
complementing the training efforts of Britain and France as well
as other African countries, USIS said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
