<HEADLINE> Singapore Records More Road Accidents in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 30 (Xinhua) -- More people died in road
accidents in Singapore last year, despite that the total number of
road accidents declined slightly compared to the previous year,
Singapore Traffic Police said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It said that a total of 247 people died in road accidents in
1997, 34 more than 1996's 213, or marking an increase of nearly 16
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Motorcyclists and their pillions were again the most vulnerable
group, making up more than half of all casualties on the roads in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The second most vulnerable group is pedestrians. And 56 percent
of the pedestrians killed in road accidents were senior citizens,
the police noted.
</P>
<P>
The Traffic Police said that the biggest cause of death by far
was speeding. Some 37 percent of all fatal accidents last year
were speed related, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
