<HEADLINE> Vietnam's 1st-Quarter Industrial Output up 13 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 30 (xinhua) -- Vietnam's industrial production
rose 13 percent during the period up to March 20 this year
compared to the same period last year, according to latest
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Production in the state-owned and foreign-invested industrial
sectors soared 11.6 percent and 21.1 percent respectively, while
the private sector reported a modest increase of 6 percent,
according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
Until March 20 this year, the production of petroleum, steel
and power -- Vietnam's key industrial products, went up by 19.6
percent, 15.6 per cent and 15.3 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Production also increased in many foreign-invested industries,
such as sugar refining, aqua-produce processing, cement,
motorbike- and refrigerater-assembling and television tube
production.
</P>
<P>
However, the statistics showed that the country's industrial
output in the said period fell short of the target set by the
government.
</P>
<P>
Among those industries that registered declines were diesel
engines (down 36.8 percent), transformers (down 16.9 percent),
tobacco (down 5 percent), electric engines (down 2.6 percent) and
fertilizer (down 2.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
The production of cement, electric fans, beer and fabrics
also slowed down during the period.
</P>
<P>
Official sources admitted that Vietnam need to work hard to
achieve high growth rates in industrial output as a result of
the tough competition in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
