<HEADLINE> Immigrants Break into UNHCR Compound in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 30 (Xinhua) -- A group of immigrants in
Malaysia forced their way into the compound of the regional office
of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
They broke into the UNHCR complex in a canvas-top lorry at
around 11 a.m., according to Kuala Lumpur police chief Kamaruddin
Ali who told reporters police had ascertained that the lorry used
by the immigrants was from Klang, a port about 30 kilometers west
from here, and that it had been driven by an Indonesian with
permanent resident status here.
</P>
<P>
By evening, the group was still in discussion with UNHCR
officials in the building on their status.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman of the office confirmed to reporters who gathered
outside the building that the UNHCR had been approached by a
number of people claiming to be Acehnese seeking refugee status
and political asylum.
</P>
<P>
"Our officials are now interviewing them to find out whether
they are of our concern or not," she said.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday hundreds of Indonesian illegal immigrants at four
holding centers including Penggeng in the country rioted as they
were about to be transferred out for deportation. 
</P>
