<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice Trade Minister Holds Talks with French Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Chen Xinhua, Chinese vice
minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, held talks
here today with Jacques Dondoux, Secretary of State to French
Ministry of Economy, Finance and Industry in Charge of External
Trade.
</P>
<P>
Chen said trade between the two countries developed smoothly
last year and that he hoped to maintain the momentum.
</P>
<P>
Dondoux said China is an important trade partner of France, and
that he hoped more French businesses would invest in China,
especially in the service sector, industry and finance.
</P>
<P>
Chen assured him that the Chinese government would keep the
"long-term and stable" policy, since the ones who made it are new
Premier Zhu Rongji and Vice Premier Li Lanqing when they served as
vice premiers in the last government.
</P>
<P>
Chen also thanked the European Union and French government for
supporting China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO),
and said he hoped France would continue to play a positive role in
this process.
</P>
<P>
In return, Dondoux suggested that China should put forward a
detailed timetable to show its sincerity and accelerate its entry
into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Noting the divergence of views, both sides agreed that it would
be wise to set up a bilateral discussion system between their
trade experts.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed possible cooperation in the fields of
nuclear power, energy, transportation and food.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics provided by Chinese Customs, France
regained its status as the third largest trade partner of China
among EU members, and the second largest exporter to China in
1997, with a total trade volume of 5.57 billion U.S. dollars and
export earnings of 3.24 billion in 1997. 
</P>
