<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Launch Campaign Against Pornographic Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 30 (Xinhua) -- A two-month special campaign
against pornographic materials will be launched throughout Hong
Kong, starting April, to enhance public awareness of the problem.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Gary Yeung Yiu-shing, assistant
commissioner for the Television and Entertainment Licensing
Authority (TELA) at a press briefing here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Yeung noted that a similar campaign was first launched last
year which had produced good results in halting the proliferation
of obscene articles, in particular pornographic video compact
discs (VCDs).
</P>
<P>
There were 1,114 prosecutions against breaches of the Control
of Obscene and Indecent Articles Ordinance, resulting in the
seizure of more than 639,000 obscene and indecent articles
including 541,000 VCDs and CD-ROMs. These represented an increase
of 25 percent in prosecution and 195 percent in seizures when
compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Yeung said: "the law enforcement agencies recognize the
importance of sustaining the effectiveness of enforcement action.
The Police, the Customs and Excise Department and TELA have
therefore agreed to conduct a two-month campaign against
pornographic materials."
</P>
<P>
During the campaign period, he said TELA will arrange talks to
schools and youth centers, and monitor articles on sale in the
market and issue summonses against publishers if their
publications do not comply with statutory requirements.
</P>
<P>
The police will concentrate their efforts at retail and
wholesale outlets, such as video and computer shops in the
districts; while the Customs and Excise Department will tackle the
problem at entry points and in the course of their copyright
protection work.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that through our intensive efforts, there will be
increased public awareness of the problem of access to
pornographic materials by young people," Yeung said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
