<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Economic Policies Producing Results: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Finance Minister
Sartaj Aziz said here Monday the government's economic policies
are producing results and the growth rate of around six percent is
to be achieved during the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
"Balance of Payments position has improved, inflation has come
down and the government's borrowing is within the limit set by the
State Bank of Pakistan," Aziz said while addressing the Official
Pakistan Privatization Summit.
</P>
<P>
He said, Pakistan's agriculture growth rate now is recorded at
five percent and the industrial growth rate at four percent.
Pakistan is hopefully to achieve the growth target of six percent
this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Pakistan Muslim League started the policy
of privatization and deregulation and achieved good results in the
period from 1991 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
The present government led by Nawaz Sharif initiated the
process after coming into power in February 1997 and made efforts
to revive the economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that the percent government introduced the process of
institutional reforms and introduced packages to revive the
agricultural and industrial sectors, and to improve the financial
sector and capital market.
</P>
<P>
The efforts are geared towards creating an international
competitive environment through privatization and investment to
achieve the growth rate of seven percent, which Pakistan had in
the 1960s, he added.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the main features of the newly announced
Investment policy, he said, the government is now trying to shift
the industry from low-value addition to high-value-addition and
have transfer of technology.
</P>
<P>
On the policy of privatization, he said, it is the key
component of the government's economic policies to improve the
operational efficiency and overall performance in different public
entities.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Privatization Summit, inaugurated by Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif Monday, was jointly organized by Pakistan's
Privatization Commission, the Ministry of Finance and the First
Conferences of U.K. The Summit has attracted more than 300
delegates from both home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chairman of the Privatization Commission Khawaja
Muhammad Asif said his organizations fully committed to the
government objectives of liberalization and deregulation of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the primary objective of this summit is to bring
together national and international investors, banking and
government officials on one platform and provide opportunities to
discuss privatization process in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the discussion will bring to fore the investment
opportunities in Pakistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
