<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over-Production of Plate Glass Unlikely to Change in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese market for plate
glass will still be a buyer's market with the supply and demand
remaining at last year's level.
</P>
<P>
According to a projection by the National Light Industry
Council, China's production of plate glass will be 168 million
standard-weight cases.
</P>
<P>
With the additional 12 million cases of plate glass in stock,
the projection says, market supply will far exceed the demand of
155 million cases.
</P>
<P>
The annual plate glass export in 1996 and 1997 was 37 million
square meters. Because of the Asian financial turmoil, this year's
export is expected to have very little impact on lowering the
supply-demand difference.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the real production increase is inconsistent with
proper, optimal growth of the plate glass industry.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, for instance, the construction of production
lines with float glass technology increased the production
capacity of plate glass in 1996 to what was planned for 2000.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, 12 such lines became operational, which resulted in a
production increase of 26 million cases. Ten lines started
operation in 1996 and 1997, turning out 23 million and 20 million
cases, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Six or seven production lines will be completed this year,
according to the council, and their combined production capacity
will be 15 million cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Provides Grant Assistance to Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has approved a technical assistance of 800,000 U.S. dollars
for Nepal to improve its drinking water supply situation in the
Kathmandu Valley, the ADB said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The assistance will be used for undertaking reforms in the
urban water supply sector to ensure water supplies in the valley,
the bank said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The bank noted that the technical assistance has been provided
in view of the weak institutional capacity and poor management of
supply and distribution of drinking water in the valley, which
need to be first improved. 
