<HEADLINE> Listeners from Six Countries Win Macao Knowledge Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Listeners from Russia, the United
States, Japan, India, Portugal and Jordan won the gold cup for the
knowledge contest of Macao which was co-organized by the China
Radio International (CRI).
</P>
<P>
Kanev Anatoli of Russia, Walter Smyth of the U.S., Goto Takashi
of Japan, Vinod Tiwari of India, Joaquim Ribeiro of Portugal and
Hassan Ali Mohamed Hassan of Jordan were selected from among
270,000 listeners who responded to the knowledge contest.
</P>
<P>
Started in October last year in 43 languages, the contest about
Macao's past, present and future and the Macao Basic Law has
attracted an avalanche of answer sheets, said Zhang Zhenhua,
president of CRI.
</P>
<P>
By March 18, CRI had received 270,000 answer sheets, including
some in Braille, from 150 countries and regions. The respondents
included government officials, lawyers, artists, journalists,
engineers, doctors, teachers, students, businessmen, farmers,
pensioners and housewives.
</P>
<P>
Qian Weichang, vice-chairman of the 9th National Committee of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC),
who arrived here on Sunday for the coming 5th anniversary of the
promulgation of the Macao Basic Law, described the contest as
successful in making Macao better known to the world.
</P>
<P>
"(The contest) has helped improve Macao's international
popularity and its good image in the world," he said in a speech
at the award-granting ceremony on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kanev Anatoli, the winner from Russia, said on behalf of the
six lucky listeners that history turned a new leaf when Hong Kong
returned to China, and Macao's return will mark another new leaf
in the oriental part of the world.
</P>
<P>
He said he had found smiling faces everywhere he went after he
arrived in Macao. That shows "people have confidence in their
future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
