<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Weaker United States and
Japanese markets led the Australian stock market to fall away on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trade, the all ordinaries index was 21.7 points
lower at 2741.0 points, off its intra-day low of 2734.0 points.
</P>
<P>
Nevitts broker Steve Mayne said the market was following the
lead from Wall Street's easing on Friday night and the drop in
Japan's Nikkei index Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones Industrial Average slipped 50.81 points to
8796.08 on Friday night. In Tokyo, the Nikkei index was 476.0
points lower at 16263.0 points. The all industrials index was 45.1
points weaker at 4695.8 points while the all resources index was
1.7 points lower at 1182.2 points.
</P>
<P>
Shares in diversified miner BHP slipped 22.9 cents to 15.421
Australian dollars after worse than expected third quarter results
were released on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In other resource stocks, Rio Tinto dropped one cent to 19.53
Australian dollars, WMC added seven and MIM was steady.
</P>
<P>
The gold sector was boosted by another rise in the gold bullion
price Monday. It was 302.40 U.S. dollars an ounce at the close of
trade in Sydney, up from Friday's finish of 301.50 dollars an
ounce.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector was weighed down by a drop in the banking
stocks, with the index shedding 68.5 points to 5608.4 points.
</P>
<P>
All of the big four banks fell away, with National off 16
cents, Commonwealth 14.1 cents cheaper, Westpac 20 lower and ANZ
also 20 lower.
</P>
<P>
Global media group News Corp slipped 15 cents while its
preferred shares tumbled 13 cents to 8.60 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Telstra installment receipts ended steady and topped turnover
with 9.79 million shares worth 38.0 million Australian dollars
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was moderate with 272.75 million shares worth
772.15 million Australian dollars (513.47 million U.S. dollars)
being traded. Falls outnumbered rises 617 to 464. 
</P>
