<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Government to Provide "Speedy News" on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong Kong
 Special Administrative Region (SAR) has begun providing a news
service "Speedy News" on the Internet, thus allowing the public to
get access to government press release almost at the same time
when the media receive the same materials, an official spokesman
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The "Speedy News" would be a major improvement to the
dissemination of information to the public by means of the
Internet, the spokesman for the Information Service Department
(ISD) of the SAR government said.
</P>
<P>
He said: "In the past, only major press releases were uploaded
manually onto the Internet after they have been issued to the
media. All items were uploaded in the form of a Daily Information
Bulletin the following day."
</P>
<P>
"With the installation of a specially-designed computer
program, press releases issued by the ISD can now be converted
into Internet file format and then be uploaded onto the government
web site automatically and in a speedy manner throughout the day,"
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, press releases in both English and
Chinese would be uploaded within five minutes after they had been
sent to the media via a dedicated network. Internet users could
choose from the daily index page the press releases, which were
arranged in the chronological order, they were interested in, he
added.
</P>
<P>
By clicking "Daily Information Bulletin," Internet users can
read press releases, speeches and transcripts of remarks and
statements made by senior officials of the SAR, statistical
reports and important announcements, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he went on to say, major press releases will be
further categorized to enable easy access to them from different
sections of the web site.
</P>
<P>
The daily "hit" at the index page of the web site has increased
10-fold from 467 in December 1995, when the home page, or the
"Government Information Center," was launched, to 5,143 last
month. Over 22,398,000 visits to all pages of the web site were
recorded during the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
