<HEADLINE> Pak PM Calls for Collective Efforts for Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif called here Monday for collective efforts to make the
privatization process a success for restructuring the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
"The government cannot on its own undertake this gigantic
effort," said Sharif while addressing the inaugural session of a
two-day Official Pakistan Privatization Summit jointly organized
by the Privatization Commission, the Finance Ministry of Pakistan
and the First Conferences of U.K..
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that "like any other transition, this process may
prove to be painful in the short run and would require
restructuring the old paradigms about economy and the state's
role."
</P>
<P>
He called for commitment and support from all the stake holders
including local business community, international investment
community, donor agencies.
</P>
<P>
The privatization process in Pakistan, he said, should be
viewed in the context of financial and fiscal difficulties being
faced by the state and the inertia that has unfortunately crept
into the public sector over the years.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is a hemorrhage in the public sector which
has to be stemmed in order for the country to pull out of the
continuous cycle of fiscal and financial indiscipline,
mismanagement and borrowing.
</P>
<P>
Strong government commitment is absolutely necessary for
successful privatization, he said, adding that commitment to the
ultimate objectives of privatization are extremely important
throughout the policy cycle.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the transaction process should be
characterized by a maximum amount of public transparency and the
privatization program should aim for maximum sustainable speed.
</P>
<P>
Underscoring benefits of the privatization efforts, Sharif said
it attracts suitable investors who provide investment, technology
transfer and management expertise.
</P>
<P>
"Incentives are created for work force to improve productivity,
and government funds can be released for the social sector and
debt retirement," he added.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the summit will highlight tremendous opportunities in
Pakistan's privatization and investment program for local and
international investors.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 delegates from 20 countries attending the summit
will hold a number of table sessions in the next two days focusing
on telecommunications, petroleum and natural resources, water and
power, infrastructure and transport, banking and finance,
industries and production sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
