<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian FM: Talks in Damascus Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said here on Monday that his talks with Syrian leaders on
issues related to the Middle East are fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi made the remarks before leaving here for Lebanon after
a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, he discussed with Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad, Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam and Foreign Minister
Farouq al-Sharaa the latest situations in the region, the issue of
south Lebanon in particular.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Khaddam Sunday evening, Kharrazi said
that Iran and Syria are concerned about Israel's expansionist
policies, its future ambitions and its long-term attempts to
change the geography in the region.
</P>
<P>
Israel's offer to pull out of south Lebanon is a trick designed
to sow the seeds of discord between Syria and Lebanon, he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said that it is ready to withdraw from south Lebanon
if the Lebanese government agrees to curb cross-border attacks on
the Jewish state by Muslim guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which agree to coordinate their stances on
key issues, have viewed it as an Israeli attempt to drive a wedge
between them and rejected the offer.
</P>
<P>
They maintain that Israel should pull back from south Lebanon,
where it set up a security zone in 1985 to allegedly protect its
northern areas from guerrilla attacks, unconditionally under the
United Nations Security Council Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister stressed that Israel's proposal is
aimed at disguising its expansionist policy which has brought the
Middle East peace process to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between Syria and Israel came to a halt two
years ago over the future of the Golan Heights, a piece of Syrian
land captured by Israel in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said the people and nations in the region are aware of
the hazards of Israel's policy and will reject its proposal to
withdraw conditionally from south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
