<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Churns Lower against Japanese Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar churned
lower Monday as a falling Japanese yen outweighed the positive
impact of a hike in gold prices, while the domestic bond market
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed at 66.68 U.S. cents, from 67.28 late
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Bank of America foreign exchange dealer Andrew Le said a rise
in the U.S. dollar against the Japanese yen had largely
contributed to the Australian dollar's weakness.
</P>
<P>
"The futures market is up a little bit - there is still hope
for a rate cut here - so that's going to combine with the fact the
U.S. dollar/yen is up to see a weaker Aussie dollar," he said.
</P>
<P>
Le said if the U.S. dollar continued to strengthen against the
yen, the Australian dollar could slide below 66 U.S. cents by the
end of the week.
</P>
<P>
The yen slipped against the U.S. dollar as concern remained
over the effectiveness of Japan's economic stimulus package
announced last week.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts are awaiting news of whether the 16 trillion
yen package will be expanded to include an income tax cut.
</P>
<P>
While events in Japan weigh heavily on the Australian dollar,
Le said the local currency was also being supported by a rise in
the price of gold.
</P>
<P>
"Gold is up above 300.00 U.S. dollars, so there is some
conflict there," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, gold bullion closed at 302.40 U.S. dollars, from a
previous close of 301.50.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed the local session at 87.65
Japanese yen from 86.99, and at 1.2104 Deutsch marks from 1.2261
on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
