<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Tourism Conference Opens in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Some 1,500 tourism and travel
industry leaders and professionals from the Asia-Pacific region
gathered here Monday to discuss the Asian financial crisis and
other challenges facing the region's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the Pacific Asia Travel
Association (PATA) 47th Annual congress, PATA Chief Executive
Officer Joe Mclnerney said the Asia-Pacific region's tourism had
enjoyed an unprecedented growth during the last decade.
</P>
<P>
Last year, he said, nearly 90 million international travelers
visited the region, up some 60 million from a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
But the region and its travel industry are facing a new chapter
filled with challenges such as economic downturn, currency
devaluation and the fire-related haze, Mclnerney said.
</P>
<P>
Mclnerney said the three-day conference will try to seek short-
and long-term solutions to these challenges.
</P>
<P>
The delegates will also discuss marketing policies, consumer
protection, strategic alliances, human resources development and
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1952 in Hawaii, PATA is a non-governmental and
non-profit association. It has 79 chapters worldwide and about
16,000 members in the region, including some 40 government
departments, 76 airlines and cruise lines, 2,200 travel and
tourism-related businesses and organizations.
</P>
<P>
The last PATA annual congress was held in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
