<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Canadian Trade Ties Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- China and Canada have enormous
potential for expanding trade and mutual investment as well as
financial and multilateral trade cooperation, foreign trade
ministers for the two countries agreed here today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Shi
Guangsheng and visiting Canadian International Trade Minister
Sergio Marchi also expressed hope during their talks that the two
countries would make a joint effort to spur bilateral cooperation
in these fields.
</P>
<P>
Shi cited last year's Sino-Canadian trade volume of four
billion U.S. dollars as modest, saying that the two governments
should push two-way trade by solving problems.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the expansion of mutual investment and
signing agreements for the protection of mutual investment at an
early date. He said that China has reached such agreements with
more than 70 countries.
</P>
<P>
At present, Canada has invested more than 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars in China and Chinese businesses have also begun to
invest in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of China's access to the World Trade Organization
(WTO), Shi said that the two countries have not reached agreement
for China's joining the WTO although many rounds of negotiations
have been held and China has made a great effort.
</P>
<P>
He said China has concluded its bilateral negotiations with
more than half of the 35 countries for its WTO entry, and that he
hoped Canada would not become one of the last to reach agreements
with China.
</P>
<P>
At present, Canada imposes anti-dumping rules on 15 kinds of
Chinese commodities, Shi said, adding that the Chinese government
does not allow its businesses to dump their products abroad.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the reason why some Chinese products are
highly competitive is that China has low processing costs, and
Canada should take this into account.
</P>
<P>
Marchi said that Canada attaches great importance to
Canadian-Chinese trade and would like to expand bilateral
cooperation in sectors of power, telecommunications, finance and
agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
