<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Threatens Boycott of Aussie Food Export Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Monday threatened a trade
boycott of Australian wheat and dairy exports unless Australia
withdraws its nearly 200 servicemen in Kuwait, a leading
Australian TV station reported.
</P>
<P>
The boycott could block Australian access to a planned 198
million U.S. dollar expansion of Iraq's dairy market and 132
million U.S. dollars in annual wheat imports under the United
Nations Oil for Food program, the Australian Broadcasting
Corporation (ABC) Television said earlier Monday.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Australian military contingent of nearly 200
servicemen in Kuwait, Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed Mehei Saleh
told ABC Television that Iraq would not do business with hostile
countries.
</P>
<P>
"We're not going to keep our trade relationship with Australia
as long as the troops are in front of the Iraqi people," Saleh
told the ABC's World program.
</P>
<P>
Australia has nearly 200 troops in Kuwait, mostly from the
elite Special Air Service regiment, which were dispatched last
month from Australia in a show of support of the United States'
threatened military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Since the introduction of the United Nations Oil for Food
program in December 1986, the Australian Wheat Board has sold 2.2
million tons of wheat to Iraq, more than 50 percent of its import
requirements, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
But Saleh warned that unless the government withdrew its
military personnel, Iraq would make a sizable cut in Australian
imports.
</P>
<P>
An Australian Wheat Board spokeswoman said Australia had a very
productive relationship with Iraq and the Iraqi Grain Board in
particular.
</P>
<P>
"The AWB has shipped about 730,000 tones so far for 1997/98 (the
financial year of 1998) and we still expect to ship about one
million tones for the year," the spokeswoman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 08:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross Proposes No U.S. Plan to Palestinians: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erekat has said United States Mideast envoy Dennis Ross has not
proposed any U.S. peace plan to the Palestinians in his current
mission, local newspaper the Jordan Times reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Until this moment the American administration has not
submitted to us any official proposal that will compel us to say
yes or no," the semi-official newspaper quoted Erekat as saying.
</P>
<P>
Erekat arrived here Sunday evening and met with Jordanian
Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Jawad Anani.
</P>
<P>
What was discussed between Ross and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat was no more than ideas of how to break the deadlock of the
peace talks between the Palestinians and Israel, Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
"We are continuing our deliberations with the American side,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived in Jerusalem last Thursday and shuttled
between Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to
win their acceptance of a proposed U.S. peace plan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly outlined a plan calling on Israel to
withdraw from 13.1 percent more of the West Bank over 12 weeks,
accompanied by Palestinian crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
However, both the Palestinians and Israel are reportedly cool
to the plan, which the U.S. has yet to make public for fear of
putting pressure on the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said the withdrawal scope is unacceptable and that
it would not pull out from more than 9 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians insist that according to U.S.-brokered
agreements signed last year, Israel should carry out three
significant pullbacks from the West Bank by summer this year.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians now have full or partial control over 27
percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said the Palestinians are extending "genuine efforts" to
get the peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
He voiced hope that the U.S. proposal would correspond to "the
precise and accurate implementation of agreements" signed between
the Palestinians and the Israelis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
