<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ranarridh Pledges to Work to Achieve Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Prince Norodom
Ranarridh, who returned to Phnom Penh earlier Monday after about
nine months of self-exile, said he would work with other parties
to achieve national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
"I shall work in cooperation with the established Cambodian
institutions, all political parties, including the Cambodian
People's Party, the National Electoral Commission... in order to
achieve national reconciliation in Cambodia and to improve the
conditions leading to free, fair and credible elections," said the
prince in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
The Prince, former first prime minister, was deposed by Hun Sen
after armed conflict between their parties in Phnom Penh on July 5
and 6.
</P>
<P>
The Phnom Penh Military Court sentenced the prince in absentia
to 35 years in prison on March 4 and 18, charging him for
illegally importing weapons and attempting to overthrow the legal
government of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
King Norodom Sihanouk granted pardon to him on March 21 after
receiving a direct appeal from the second Prime Minister Hun Sen,
making him eligible to participate in the general elections
scheduled for July 26.
</P>
<P>
Ranarridh's FUNCINPEC party and the Cambodian People's Party
led by Hun Sen are expected to be the main rivals in the elections.
</P>
<P>
About two thousand people held demonstrations Saturday in the
city against the return of Prince Ranarridh and his top military
commanders, which was accompanied by a top-level delegation
including U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan's Special
representative to Cambodia, Lakhan Mehrotra. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
