<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian to Revise Land-Use Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 30 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province,
facing overpopulation and a shortage of cultivated land, will
revise its land-use plan this year, a local official said today.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin Fanglei, director of the provincial land
administration bureau, the new plan would help stop the decline of
cultivated land caused by rapid economic development.
</P>
<P>
The province also plans to launch an overall check on the one
million hectares of basic farmland this year to ensure that 80
percent of the cultivated land remains under top protection.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, land-use management will be strengthened, according
to Lin. He added that land administration departments will
participate in the approval process for new construction projects
regarding land use.
</P>
<P>
With a per-capita arable land of 0.04 hectares, the province
has to import one billion kilograms of grain every year from other
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The occupation of arable land for non-farming purposes has
worsened the situation. A recent survey shows that, in the past
seven years, half of more than 700,000 hectares of construction
formerly was farmland.
</P>
<P>
The province has intensified its law enforcement in land
use. So far, the local government has handled 40,000 cases of the
illegal use of land and taken back land-use rights for 200
hectares.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 08:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat to Discuss U.S. Peace Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat will hold talks with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak on a U.S. peace plan in Egypt's Red Sea resort of
Sharm el-Shiekh on Monday, the Al-Akhbar newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Arafat will also brief Mubarak on his three
rounds of meetings with United States Mideast envoy Dennis Ross,
the Arabic-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived in Israel last Thursday and reportedly shuttled
between Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in a
bid to win their acceptance of the U.S. plan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly formulated a plan calling on Israel to
withdraw from 13.1 percent of the West Bank over 12 weeks, linked
to Palestinian crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians and Israel are cool to the plan, which the
U.S. has yet to make public for fear of putting pressure on the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said the withdrawal scope is unacceptable and that
it would pull out from no more than 9 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians insist that Israel carry out three significant
pullbacks by summer this year under U.S.-brokered agreements
signed last year between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ross will also travel to Sharm el-Sheikh on Monday
to hold talks with Mubarak and Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on the
stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ross' visit to Egypt is aimed at highlighting the U.S. idea to
push forward the peace process, Moussa told reporters on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He rejected claims that Egypt may pressurize the Palestinians
into accepting U.S. ideas to break the peace impasse, stressing
that Egypt would accept nothing short of a balanced peace.
</P>
<P>
"Our job is not to offer the Palestinians on a plate to the
(Israeli) Likud government. Egypt can not do this nor does it
accept it. All that Egypt can do is to make reasoning when it gets
convinced," the Egyptian foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed Egypt's readiness to cooperate with the U.S.
proposal, which he said should go in line with the signed
agreements based on the land-for-peace principle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
