<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- From 150,000 to 180,000 people demonstrated last Saturday in
Paris, Montpellier, Grenoble and a dozen other major cities against
the alliance between rightwing politicians and National Front in the
regional elections. Meanwhile, President Jacques Chirac will begin
on Monday consultations on modernizing the public life of France in
the wake of the turmoil in the regional elections.
</P>
<P>
-- The United States threatens to withdraw from the Middle East
 peace process and to let Israel and Palestinians to deal with
each other all alone. According to the Israeli daily Ma'ariv on
Sunday, U.S. Secretary of State Madelein Albright told American
Jewish leaders in a telephone conversation that the United States
can not go on like this as a mediator, and one of the possibility
is a pure and simple withdrawal from the process.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Following turmoil in the regional elections caused by the
alliance between the National Front and some rightwing politicians,
President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin are
entering a speeding track in a competition for initiatives to
modernize the political life of France. Chirac will begin
consultations with the heads of 13 mainstream rightwing political
parties, while the Socialist government has announced that it will
present a draft law to reform the polling method in regional
elections before Summer.
</P>
<P>
-- Four years after the genocide in Rwanda, the policy adopted by
former French President Francois Mitterrand for the Great Lakes
region still remains a mystery. No official investigation has been
launched into the downing of the French military helicopter which
carried the presidents of Rwanda and Burundin on April 6, 1994. The
killing of the two presidents triggered the massacres in Rwanda.
</P>
