<HEADLINE> Uganda Publishes Science Textbooks in Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Institute of Languages at
Makerere University in Uganda has published science textbooks for
lower primary children in local languages, The Monitor reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The textbooks are to be introduced as a part of textbooks for
Universal Primary Education (UPE), the paper added.
</P>
<P>
UPE is a scheme of the country to provide free education for
four children for every family.
</P>
<P>
The new science books are published in two local languages --
Luganda and Runyakitara, with the former used in the central part
of the country while the latter is spoken by people in southwest
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has more than 40 tribes. Every tribe has its own
language so that it is hard for an uneducated person to have a
conversation with others from another tribe.
</P>
<P>
In Uganda, school children start their schooling in English,
while local languages are used in middle school.
</P>
<P>
Many lower primary class children complain they have
difficulty to understand some content of their syllabus in
English.
</P>
<P>
The science textbooks were translated by local scholars under
the sponsorship of senior lecturers of the Language Institute of
Makerere University, the most famous university in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
