<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Plans to Visit Iran Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 30 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela has reiterated to maintain good relations with
Iran, saying that he would visit Iran soon, apparently another
gesture to maintain his independent foreign deplomatic policy.
</P>
<P>
"I will visit Iran shortly and I do not hide those things,"
Mandela told CNN television Sunday hours after seeing off
visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said last Friday that he would not betray friends who
had helped the country in apartheid era, such as Libya, Iran and
Cuba, three countries Washington treats as pariah states.
</P>
<P>
In his latest remarks, Mandela said "Libya, Cuba and Iran are
my friends," noting those countries' support for the
anti-apartheid struggle in South Africa "when the United States,
as other Western Powers, at the time of struggle were really
helping our enemy."
</P>
<P>
Mandela also repeated his opposition to the Growth and
Opportunity Bill on trade relations which is before the U.S.
Senate. The bill offers trade bonuses to African countries that
back democracy and apply International Monetary Fund reforms.
</P>
<P>
"We resist any attempt by any country to impose conditions on
our freedom of trade. That we cannot accept. And the provisions
of this bill will restrict our freedom to trade with countries,
something that I found totally unacceptable," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has several times upset Washington since he took power
after the first non-racial elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In September 1996, then Iranian President Ali Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani visited South Africa and the two countries have been
in good relations.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also expressed willingness to play a role in resolving
differences between Washington and those regimes it opposes.
</P>
<P>
"The enemies of the United States are not our enemies... We
are ready, and there are many influential heads of state who are
ready to help ensuring that the relations between the U.S. and
those countries are sorted out peacefully in a way that will
please both countries.
</P>
<P>
"The Unites States of America plays an important role in world
affairs but... American foreign policy should be consistent with
the provision of the United Nations Charters which call upon all
the countries to settle their disputes by peaceful means," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, the first American president ever to visit South
Africa, spent four days in the country. He left Johannesburg
Sunday for Botswana, the fifth country visited on his six-nation
African tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
