<HEADLINE> Stocks Plunge in Tokyo After Early Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices plunged in Tokyo on
Monday with the key Nikkei index losing more than 500 points just
before the close of the session, on diminishing expectations that
the government will use public funds to prop it up.
</P>
<P>
The 225-issue Nikkei average on the First Section of the Tokyo
Stock Exchange finished at 16,263.04, down 476.22 points or 2.84
percent from last Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
The index jumped to a high of 17,009.89 soon after the market
opened, but plummeted toward closing to hit a low of 16,238.56.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index, covering all issues
on the major section, dropped 17.28 points or 1.37 percent to
1,241.27.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section went up to an estimated 360 million
shares from Friday's 300 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo stocks rose more than 200 points early in the morning
over a news report that the Japanese government and the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party plan to continue special income tax cuts
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
But the market lost impetus amid the yen's depreciation in the
foreign exchange market, and turned negative in the afternoon,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
Institutional investors, which had waited until the last minute
for a boost in the market by a public fund infusion for the fiscal
year-end, began selling on disappointment, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,327 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outweighed gainers 791 to 317, with 123 remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
