<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 08:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Israeli Rightwing Camp Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 30 (Xinhua) -- As United States peace envoy
Dennis Ross is continuing his peace mediation here, Israeli
rightwing camp threatened to topple the government if it succumbs
to the U.S. pressure on Israeli further redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Ross held a third round of talks Sunday night separately with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat in an attempt to
pin down the size of Israeli second further redeployment in the
West Bank. No breakthrough was reported as the talks stalled over
Israeli demand for reciprocity from the PNA.
</P>
<P>
While Ross was trying to persuade the two sides to come close
on the scope of Israeli pullout, a leading rightwing party within
Israeli ruling coalition issued a strong warning to Netanyahu
against relinquishing land.
</P>
<P>
The leadership of National Religious Party (NRP) held a
special meeting Sunday night and formulated a list of demands for
Netanyahu's talks with Ross. Top on the list was a demand that
Israel should not give up more than 35 percent of the West Bank in
a final settlement. This means that the second redeployment could
not exceed over 9 percent, which the U.S. and the PNA have both
regarded as too little.
</P>
<P>
The hardline party made it clear that if its demands were not
met, then it would not stay in the coalition. NRP lawmaker Hanan
Porat claimed that the U.S. proposal of 13.1 percent redeployment
was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Porat, as well as two other NRP lawmakers Nissim Slomiansky
and Zvi Hendel, is a member of the Land of Israel Front that is
strongly opposed to giving up larger part of West Bank. The Front
includes 10 lawmakers from different parties.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, hardline Likud lawmaker and a Front member Zeev
Begin made it clear that he and other members would topple the
government if it hands over more land to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the inaction on the part of
Netanyahu in making decision on the second redeployment is
largely due to the strong opposition from his rightwing coalition
partners. The coalition is holding only one-seat majority in the
120-member Knesset (Parliament), and it cannot afford to alienate
any coalition partner.
</P>
<P>
One scenario could be that even the Land of Israel Front voted
against the government over the redeployment, the opposition
Labor Party would possibly come to rescue by voting for it.
</P>
<P>
But in this case, Netanyahu might have to renew his call for
setting up a national unity government with the Labor in order to
push forward the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the centrist coalition party Yisrael Baaliya issued
a call Sunday for achieving national unity so to thwart the
balckmailing by rightwing parties led by the NRP. Yisrael
Baaliya's lawmaker Roman Bronfman said he would begin a series of
talks this week to facilitate the creation of a national unity
government.
</P>
<P>
Bronfman reasoned that with such hawkish party like the NRP in
the government, it would be impossible for Netanyahu to continue
the peace process. The U.S. has declared that the peace process is
nearing its end and Washington could wash its hands off the
process, so it is high time for settling up a unity government.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Labor has been cool towards the suggestion of
joining a unity government with the Likud. The head of Labor
reaction team in the Knesset (Parliament) Dalia Itzik commented
on Bronfman's call by saying: "Labor has no desire to join a
Netanyahu-led government. Our aim is to bring him down as soon as
possible and go immediately to new elections - the sooner, the
better." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0145 </DOCNO>
