<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Domestic Debt Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's domestic debt rose to
2.4 billion U.S. Dollars in January this year compared to 2.03
billion Dollars in January 1997, according to the latest issue of
Monthly Economic Review.
</P>
<P>
The publication issued by the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) said
that the increase in domestic debt over the past year followed
increased government borrowing to meet budgetary financing
requirements and external debt repayments.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector was the government's major creditor with
the new credit from the sector amounting to 1.3 billion Dollars
or 56.4 percent of the debt stock, it stated.
</P>
<P>
Credit to government from the non-bank sector was 1.06 billion
Dollars or 43.6 percent of the outstanding credit, it added.
</P>
<P>
Among the government securities which were the main form of
borrowing, CBK noted, Treasury Bills proved to be the most
popular debt instrument with the outstanding stock of Treasury
Bills at 2.01 billion Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
