<HEADLINE> Manila Seeks Foreign Help in Dousing Forest Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
seeking the assistance of foreign countries to douse the on-going
forest fires in the western provinces of Palawan and Davao del
Norte, Defense Secretary Fortunato Abat said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Abat told the country's DZBB radio station Monday morning that
the government is seeking the help of Australia and Canada to put
out the raging forest fire.
</P>
<P>
The National Disaster Coordinating Council has released 3
million pesos (79,365 U.S. dollars) to fight the fire, he said,
but the money could not be enough.
</P>
<P>
Abat said that the cloud-seeding conducted by the Philippine
Air Force over the area affected by the fire had no effect and
additional troops would be sent to the area to help in fighting
the forest fire.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Palawan Police Provincial Office director
Elnora Bernardino told the DZMM radio station that the forest fire
in Palawan could have affected some 20,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Bernardino said that by Sunday night, the forest fire has
lapped up at least 18,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
In Davao del Norte, the forest fire that started on March 13 in
Marasugan had already affected 200 hectares of forest of the
Pacific Cordillera Mountain Range. 
</P>
</TEXT>
