<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Initiates Airport Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is taking
active measures, including the adoption of a share-holding system
and Sino-foreign joint management, to upgrade its heavily
debt-ridden airport industry.
</P>
<P>
Revitalizing airports is an effort to help the civil aviation
industry respond to the growth of national economy, said Xia
Xinghua, director of Department of System Restructuring and
Regulation of the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC).
</P>
<P>
Xia noted, in an exclusive interview with Xinhua, that CAAC
will issue a regulation late this year. In line with the
regulation, foreign investors will be allowed to enter more
sectors in airports and can participate in high-level management.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign investment still cannot surpass 49 percent of
the registered capital of an aviation enterprise, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tianhe Airport of Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei
Province, is making preparations for the introduction of funds and
advanced management experience from a Hong Kong-based enterprise.
</P>
<P>
The test airport will become the first airport involving
Sino-foreign joint management, Xia said.
</P>
<P>
"Joint management provides an opportunity for airports to
deepen reform and open wider to the outside world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Airports are basic for commercial use, and the government will
put its major investment into air traffic management and flight
operations such as runways.
</P>
<P>
Borrowing, lending and renting will be introduced to build and
manage the terminal area. Foreign investment will also be
encouraged in the areas of ground service, aircraft maintenance,
and hotels.
</P>
<P>
Xia said that one unsolved problem in the construction of
airports is how to use foreign funds efficiently for a long period
of time.
</P>
<P>
Airports call for huge investments, ranging from 1-to-10
billion yuan, but they also are public facilities serving air
carriers instead of a production unit. The length of time required
to gain returns on investment has depreciated the attraction of
airport industry for overseas investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
