</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Initiates Airport Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xia also noted that more airports will be offered on stock
exchanges to gain funds for expansion at low cost and to introduce
share-holding systems.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Capital International Airport and New Baiyun Airport of
Guangzhou have been absorbed in the CAAC plan for share-holding
renovation. Capital Airport also will be listed on overseas stock
markets.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen, Shanghai Hongqiao International and Shenzhen Huangtian
airports were listed on domestic stock exchanges recently, gaining
several billion yuan for expansion and renovation.
</P>
<P>
Shen Yuankang, deputy director-general of CAAC, said airports
with good conditions are supported to be listed on stock
exchanges, and big airports can be listed overseas to lower debts.
</P>
<P>
The CAAC investment policy also calls for the engagement of
local government. Only a dozen out of 124 existing airports under
CAAC received local government funding.
</P>
<P>
"For the airports that mainly serve a local economy, the
investment from local government is still not enough. It is hard
to maintain the demanded growth of the airport industry with the
mere funds from the central government," said Xia, adding that
local governments will obtain more management rights if they
set aside more funds.
</P>
<P>
According to a CAAC project, China will build, expand, or
upgrade all the airports in provincial capitals and municipalities
during the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), at a cost of
nearly 100 billion yuan. In 1998, 13 airports, including Guangzhou
New Baiyun and Hangzhou Xiaoshan, will be built and expanded.
</P>
<P>
"To get the huge investment, the airport investment system
should go on the track of reform," Xia said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the airport management system should be
transferred from direct management by airport itself. Airport
commercial areas should adopt a competitive mechanism such as
renting, contracting, and selling special management rights to
promote its development.
</P>
<P>
Another source said the CAAC is spreading a standard management
system in airports and airlines, which specifies industrial
standards for enterprises and different levels of managers and
employees in an effort to increase the industry's efficiency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0160 </DOCNO>
