<HEADLINE> Prince Ranarridh Returns to Phnom Penh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's former co-premier
Prince Norodom Ranarridh returned to Phnom Penh Monday after about
nine months of self-exile.
</P>
<P>
He was welcomed by officials from his FUNCINPEC party and
supporters at Phnom Penh's Pochentong International Airport after
he emerged from a Thai Airways International flight, which left
Bangkok at 0400 GMT.
</P>
<P>
The prince was accompanied by a top-level delegation including
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan's special representative to
Cambodia, Lakhan Mehrotra.
</P>
<P>
This was Ranarridh's first return after he was deposed by
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen last July in a wake of a bloody
military crashes between the Hun-Sen-controlled army and
Ranarridh's supporters.
</P>
<P>
The prince will participate in the July 26 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Ranarridh was sentenced to a total of 35 years in prison for
illegally importing and transporting arms and some other charges
at two trials by default earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
King Norodom Sihanouk, after receiving a direct appeal from
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen, granted the prince pardon on March
21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
