<HEADLINE> Danish Govt to Aid Zimbabwe in Environmental </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Danish government will
provide 425 million Zimbabwean Dollars (25 million U.S. Dollars)
within the next four years to support environmental management
programs in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The Danish International Development Agency said in a
statement at the weekend that the objective of funding, extended
to other countries in southern Africa, was to assist the region
in implementing sustainable environmental projects, The Herald
daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Priority areas for possible assistance include training and
information activities to improve and widen the region's
awareness of the importance of environmental protection and
sustainable development, transfer of technology and expertise,
support for institutional and administrative capacity-building in
regional, national and local institutions that administer
environmental related issues, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
"In order to enhance the quality of this assistance and
achieve a greater degree of focus, continuity and sustainability,
a gradual transition is taking place in keeping with the strategy
for Danish development assistance towards the year 2000," said
the statement. 
</P>
