<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross Says U.S. Peace Plan Under Refinement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 30 (Xinhua) -- United States Middle East Peace
Coordinator Dennis Ross will report back to Washington about
"refinements" to the U.S. peace plan, that had emerged from
several rounds of talks with Israeli and Palestinian leaders,
Israel Radio reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived in the region last Thursday in efforts to
break the deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process, held
a third round of talks with Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat late Sunday night in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Ross told reporters that refinements had been
made to the U.S. peace initiative, which reportedly calls on
Israel to hand over 13.1 percent of the West Bank to the
Palestinians, linked to the fulfillment of the Palestinian
commitments to Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
Ross said that he is going to report the development to
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, who will decide the next move to advance the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The peace envoy stressed that he had held "thorough" talks
with Israeli and Palestinian leaders on the peace talks, which
have been stalled for months over the extent of Israeli troop's
next pullback in the territories.
</P>
<P>
But Ross did not mention any concrete progress in the
talks. And Arafat, who looked angry, refused to make comments on
his meeting with Ross.
</P>
<P>
Before Ross went to Gaza, he also met with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on Sunday in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, Netanyahu's communications adviser, said the
meeting focused on Israel's security requirements and the
reciprocity issue, in contrast to early reports that they would
discuss the scope of the Israeli redeployment.
</P>
<P>
He said that during his first two rounds of talks with Ross,
Arafat did not give a positive response to the implementation of
the Palestinian undertakings on security matters. "Without
reciprocity, there can be no talk of percentage," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ross intends to fly to Egypt on Monday morning to discuss
the peace process with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
return to Israel in the afternoon for another meeting with
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
However, no further meetings are scheduled with Arafat
because Ross is due to visit the Netherlands on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
