<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Participate in SADC Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will participate in the
second Southern African Development Community (SADC) joint
peacekeeping military exercise in South Africa in November this
year, The Herald daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed Exercise Blue Crane, the peacekeeping operation to be
held with the assistance of the British military advisory team,
will bring together soldiers from other SADC member countries for
extensive training.
</P>
<P>
South African High Commissioner to Zimbabwe Kingsley Mamabolo
confirmed at the weekend that his country would host the second
peacekeeping military exercise.
</P>
<P>
South Africa participated in the Exercise Blue Hungwe in
Nyanga in Zimbabwe last year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
According to Mamabolo, the exercise was an initiative of the
Zimbabwe defense force and was supported by the British military
advisory team.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa viewed its participation in the exercise as an
opportunity to exchange information, to share experiences, to
standardize operation procedures and to interact with
counterparts in SADC," he said.
</P>
<P>
Exercise Blue Hungwe, hosted by Zimbabwe last April, was the
first-ever joint military exercise grouping eight SADC countries
and was hailed as a milestone which opened a chapter in cementing
regional cooperation and co-existence in the field of defense.
</P>
<P>
On defense relations between Zimbabwe and South Africa,
Mamabolo said the two countries had made significant progress in
the areas of bilateral training programs and joint operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
