<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Learn Lessons From Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- A signed article in the
today's Beijing-based "China Daily" said it is high time
for China to draw a lesson from the stumbling tigers and try to
keep its economy from being affected.
</P>
<P>
The article, written by Gao Shangquan, a noted Chinese
economist and former Vice-Minister of the State Commission for
Economic Restructuring, said that speculative activities against
Southeast Asian currencies triggered the financial turmoil in the
region last July.
</P>
<P>
However, weak points in the fundamentals and financial systems
of Southeast Asian economies were mainly responsible for the
nations' troubles.
</P>
<P>
These weak points include economic bubbles, loose regulation
over the financial sector, a large proportion of non-performing
bank loans, overdue dependence on short-term foreign debts and
huge deficits for balance of international payment, Gao said.
</P>
<P>
China must focus on the following seven issues:
</P>
<P>
-- The government should avoid being too closely and frequently
involved in business activities. In addition, market-based
relations should be established between banks and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
-- Large-scale enterprises should be built with market-based
instruments. Market forces, instead of the government, should
decide whether two or more firms are to merge into a giant group.
</P>
<P>
-- The government should help its state-owned commercial banks
cut the bad assets and help banks shake off their huge bad loans
in order to effectively avoid financial risks.
</P>
<P>
-- China should adjust its economic structure and promote
material economy, technological renovation, consummation of
industrial make-up and enhancement of labor productivity.
</P>
<P>
-- The state should fix its structure of foreign
investment. The influx of short-term foreign debt and foreign
investment in securities should be limited.
</P>
<P>
-- The country should strengthen regulation over the financial
sector and further improve its system of financial supervision and
control.
</P>
<P>
-- It is important to enhance public awareness of financial
risks and confidence in the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
