<HEADLINE> Farm Owners Contract Wasteland in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Fei Wenjing, a 22-year-old woman
living in the suburbs of Tai'an, a city in east China's Shandong
Province, earned more than one million yuan from her contracted
pig farm last year.
</P>
<P>
Fei, a college graduate, said the secret to her success besides
her knowledge and interests in modern farmland exploitation was
the opportunity provided her by the government's preferential
policy.
</P>
<P>
According to an official from the provincial agricultural
administration, Shandong has auctioned the operating rights for
134,000 hectares of wasteland and transferred the rights for
67,000 hectares of land to more than 100,000 private farmland
owners like Fei.
</P>
<P>
In addition to private ownership, cooperative operations of
farmland in form of share-holding, technology and production
materials have been introduced to the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The farmers each claimed an averaged 1.3 hectares of land and
are mainly engaged in growing grain, vegetables, oil-bearing
crops, fruit, flowers and herbs as well as animal husbandry and
aquatic breeding.
</P>
<P>
The official said most of the farmers are maintaining close
ties with research institutions and agronomists in seeding,
growing and marketing. The machinery used in agricultural
production on this kind of private farmlands is 30 percent higher
than the provincial average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
