<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Region Uses Cotton By-products for Feed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Scientists in northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region have successfully turned cotton
stalks, seed dregs and other by-products into a major feed source
for livestock in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The region, China's largest cotton producer, turns out more
than a million tons of cotton annually and has large amounts of
cotton by-products. But local people used the poison-bearing
cotton by-products either as firewood or fertilizer, which
contributed to environmental pollution.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago the regional Academy of Agricultural Sciences
began work on a project concerning cotton-stalk ensilage and
harvesting machines.
</P>
<P>
Now the agronomists have invented cotton-stalk harvesting
machines, cotton-stalk silage technology, cotton-seed dregs and
hulls synthetic fodder, and detoxified cotton protein feed. This
paved the way to change cotton by-products into edible forage.
</P>
<P>
The achievements have been tried in nine pilot areas involving
145,000 tons of feed production and 620 related farm machines, and
widely acclaimed by cotton growers and livestock farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0179 </DOCNO>
