<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Removes Energy Minister, Takes Measures to Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina on Sunday removed Energy and Mineral Resources Minister M.
Noor Uddin Khan as part of her move to streamline the country's
power supply system.
</P>
<P>
Noor Uddin Khan was made minister without portfolio, according
to a Cabinet Division circular issued on Sunday. The circular did
not give details.
</P>
<P>
No replacement has been announced so far, and Hasina is
expected to take over the charge of the energy minister for the
time being to solve the electricity problem, reports said.
</P>
<P>
At a cabinet meeting last week, Hasina expressed her
dissatisfaction over the performance of the Energy Ministry and
its failure to improve the power supply in the country.
</P>
<P>
The country has a power shortage of 450 megawatts everyday
against the minimum nationwide demand for 2200 megawatts,
according to officials with the Power Development Board (PDB). The
capital city of Dhaka alone is facing 170 to 180 megawatts of
shortage every day on average, against the peak hour demand of 625
megawatts, and as a result, power is cut off in many parts of the
city three or four times a day.
</P>
<P>
The government is under strong criticism for its failure to
solve the power crisis, and local business chambers, foreign
investors, organizations and ordinary residents have been strongly
demanding for a solution of the power crisis.
</P>
<P>
The PDP blamed the sudden fall in gas pressure, falling water
level and the closing down of some power generating units for
routine maintenance for the low power generation, leading to
massive loadshedding.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the PDB said the change in the Energy Ministry
would not help improve the situation of power supply. "It is not
the fault of the minister. We simply do not have the capacity of
generating adequate electricity to meet the growing demand," a
senior official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The power crisis is unlikely to end until the end of the year
when some power plants will be put into operation, PDB officials
said.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to increase power supply, the government on Sunday
took a number of decisions to streamline the country's power
supply system, including the establishment of inter-agency
coordination, proper load management, reducing frequent
loadshedding and generation of additional electricity.
</P>
<P>
And a monitoring cell to supervise round-the-clock the power
situation across the country has been set up at the prime
minister's office, to be managed by the Armed Forces Division,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister has given a directive to increase the
generation capacity of the existing power plants through proper
management and renovation, and has directed authorities concerned
to giver prior notice to the clients regarding timings of
loadshedding, according to the reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
