<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Remove Tariff on IT Products by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will eliminate
tariff on information technology (IT) products, ranging from
computers, semi-conductors, telecommunication equipment and
semi-conductor manufacturing equipment by the year 2000,
International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The elimination of tariff on IT products will provide better
market access for Malaysia's exports, she told reporters after
opening a two-day workshop on "The implication of Uruguay Round
Agreement for international trade in technology-based products"
here.
</P>
<P>
As such, it would be beneficial for the Malaysian industry to
seek market opportunities for contract manufacturing, she said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said another area worth considering is in
developing niche products and downstream value-added applications
such as in software development.
</P>
<P>
"The industry needs to build its competitive advantage by
entering into joint-ventures and smart partnership that will
promote transfer of technology," she added.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is an important trader in IT products, accounting for
about five percent share of the global IT trade. Its current
strength in the IT sector is in the area of component
manufacturing and assembly.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Malaysia's exports of IT related products totaled 79.6
billion ringgit (about 22.359 billion U.S. dollars) while imports
were 65.6 billion ringgit (about 18.427 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In order to further enhance its exports of IT products,
Malaysia became a signatory to the declaration of trade in IT
products or the Information Technology Agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
