<HEADLINE> Tornadoes Hit Southern Minnesota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Tornadoes leveled homes across
southern Minnesota in the United States on Sunday, killing at
least one person and injuring more than a dozen.
</P>
<P>
Hardest hit was the towns of St. Peter in south-central
Minnesota and Comfrey in southwestern Minnesota, where tornadoes
barreled through the middle of town, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
A 6-year-old boy died and 10 others from St. Peter were
hospitalized, two in critical condition. Eleven people were taken
from Comfrey to a hospital in nearby Springfield, five of whom
were discharged.
</P>
<P>
In St. Peter, with a population of 10,000, dozens of homes were
destroyed and several buildings on the campus of Gustavus Adolphus
College were damaged.
</P>
<P>
In Lonsdale, about 30 miles south of Minneapolis, another
tornado touched down and destroyed some homes, witnesses said. In
Wisconsin, a tornado touched down without damage in Maxville.
</P>
