<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loans Used To Control Soil Erosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Gansu Province in northwest China
has made remarkable progress in using World Bank loans to improve
soil erosion in the Loess Plateau.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the province had brought an
840-square-kilometer area of soil erosion under control,
accounting for 65 percent of the planned coverage.
</P>
<P>
In 1994 an eight-year World Bank project was introduced into
the province, aimed at improving a 1,506-square-kilometer area of
soil erosion involving 578 million yuan of investment, of which 40
million U.S. dollars will be provided by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The project covers six counties and cities with 4,300 square
kilometers and 510,000 people. By last year, 370 million yuan had
been spent on the project to increase 16,000 hectares of terraced
fields, 38,000 hectares of forests and 20,000 hectares of
grassland.
</P>
<P>
The Malian River watershed, one of the most serious
soil-erosion areas, is one example. Local farmers have raised
per-capita grain production from 383 kilograms to 410 kilograms
because of the improved environment and farmland.
</P>
<P>
Soil-erosion area amounted to more than 70 percent of the
640,000-square-kilometer Loess Plateau, depositing 1.6 billion
tons of silt into the Yellow River annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Herdsmen Say Farewell to Nomadic Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- More than 150,000 herdsmen and
their families in Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region have bid
farewell to a traditional nomadic way of life by settling down to
a fixed address.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents 67 percent of the herding households in
Xinjiang, which is one of the five major pastoral regions of China.
</P>
<P>
Weather conditions on the vast grassland are severe, making the
life of a herdsman difficult, especially in winter. In 1986 the
autonomous region began to take measures to help settle the
nomadic population.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has earmarked funds to assist the
settlement scheme apart from providing preferential terms such as
tax reduction.
</P>
<P>
The scheme has helped many herdsmen previously living in the
high mountains to find new houses on the plains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Province Encourages More Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Hainan Province has worked out new
policies encouraging further overseas investment in a bid to
reverse a decline in overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Direct overseas investment has dropped for three consecutive
years in the island province, which is also a special economic
zone.
</P>
<P>
Under the new proposed terms, the province will enlarge its
right of approval for larger overseas-funded projects.
</P>
<P>
The province is also asking to have the right to approve
Sino-foreign joint development of offshore oil, fishing and the
exploration of mineral resources, which now are in the hands of
the central government.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has also pledged to let overseas investors enjoy the
same treatment enjoyed as local investors.
</P>
<P>
Measures also call for boosting economic and trade cooperation
with Hong Kong and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
According to provincial authorities, some of the above policies
have already been authorized. 
</P>
