<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Teachers Abandon Jobs Due to Won's Devaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 30 (Xinhua) -- More employed foreigners teaching
English in South Korea are giving up their jobs as their pays have
sharply fallen in value resulting from the devaluation of the won
caused by the ongoing financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In the past two months, 126 of 856 foreign teachers, whose pays
stood at between 1.4 million won (about 1,000 U.S. dollars) and
1.8 million won (about 1,300 dollars) each month, quitted their
jobs in the economic crisis-engulfed country.
</P>
<P>
Since last October, the South Korean won has depreciated more
than 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year saw the country's per capita income down to 9,400
dollars from the previous year's 10,548 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts and economists predicted that the nation's per capita
income will further drop to some 6,600 dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
All foreign teachers, whose contracts are to expire in July,
were hired by the nation as part of the efforts last year to
improve English education for the students of junior and senior
schools in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Education Ministry originally planned to hire 1,200 foreign
teachers for English education this year.
</P>
<P>
But the number will have to be reduced due to the austerity
measures required by the International Monetary Fund, which agreed
last December to extend a rescue loan of 57 billion dollars to
South Korea in the coming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Stock Exchange to Rate Advisers' Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) will launch a "credit rating" system for institutions
offering financial advisory services for listed companies, the
Bangkok Post said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The system is aimed at encouraging greater responsibility among
the financial institutions and investment banks involved, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
SET President Singh Tangtatswas said ratings would encourage
development of better quality services by financial institutions,
and indirectly lead to improved protection of investors.
</P>
<P>
Many listed firms have turned to local finance firms and
investment banks for advice on rehabilitation programs, debt
restructuring and raising new capital.
</P>
<P>
According to Singh, many companies had suffered damages from
poorly crafted, impractical rehabilitation plans suggested by
their advisers.
</P>
<P>
Under the "credit rating" system, if results of a
rehabilitation plan are found to be unsatisfactory, with
performance at, for example, just 20 percent of original forecast,
market regulators will order an immediate downgrade in the rating
of the adviser.
</P>
<P>
Regulators will also suggest that the Securities and Exchange
Commission withdraw the licenses of poorly rated firms, preventing
advisers from providing services to other listed firms in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Market officials will also warn firms seeking advisory services
or launching a new public offering to avoid financial institutions
with a poor rating.
</P>
<P>
The system is part of SET's efforts to encourage the
development of good governance among listed companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
