<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia-IMF Meeting Fails to Solve Private Sector's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The question of the private
sector's foreign debts remains unsolved as the talks between
Indonesia and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on the
country's economic reform entered the 12th day on Sunday, a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
"Frankly speaking, the question of the private sector's foreign
debts is the most difficult thing to solve. But I am sure it can
be solved soon. We are in constant contact with the IMF
headquarters in Washington, the U.S. Treasury Secretary and the
Japanese Finance Minister," Coordinating Minister for Economy,
Finance and Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At the end of December last year, Indonesia's foreign debts
totaled 137.424 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The talks have reached the final stage, but ways and means to
tackle the 74 billion dollar private debts have yet to reach a
conclusion, official Antara news agency Monday quoted the minister
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The settlement of the private sector's foreign debts is
included in the five-point agenda discussed at the meeting to
review Indonesia's economic reform.
</P>
<P>
In the last 12 days, both sides have been discussing corporate
debt, bank restructuring, budget and subsidies, monetary policy
and structural reform. "Talks on the other four areas are mostly
concluded...only some details remain," Ginandjar said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Indonesia proposed to follow the "Mexican Model" in
settling its private foreign debts. The IMF team led by its
Asia-Pacific Director Hubert Neiss has agreed to the proposal in
principle.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah (national currency) has been under severe
pressure since July last year, plunging to its lowest level of
17,000 to the greenback in January, compared to 2,450 rupiah in
the pre-crisis period in July. It is trading at about 8,300 per
dollar now.
</P>
<P>
This has caused most indebted companies to become technical
bankrupt as their foreign debts surpass their equity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
