<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Seeks Help to Restore Temple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka sought help from India
and Germany to restore the Dalada Maligama (Tooth Relic Temple) in
the central mountain city of Kandy, which was damaged last January
by a Tamil rebel vehicle bomb, official sources here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The entrance, outer wall, roof and some other parts of the
temple sustained extensive damage due to the explosion, which
killed at least 17 people and injured many others.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner of the Archeological Department Shiran
Deraniyagala was quoted as saying that the moonstone and other
portions of immense artistic, archeological and cultural value
were also destroyed by the explosion.
</P>
<P>
His department was doing all it could to restore all sections
destroyed in the explosion. Photographs of the damaged parts had
been presented to Indian Director General of Archeology Professor
Ravo for advice, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Assistance had similarly been sought from Germany.
</P>
<P>
The temple, where Sri Lanka Buddhists go to pay their homage to
the sacred relic believed to be belonging to the Buddha, is
regarded as one of the most important symbols of the island
country.
</P>
<P>
The reconstruction work is estimated to take about two years to
complete, according to local press reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
