<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire in National Park Brought Under Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Firefighters have brought under
control the blazes that ravaged the Doi Inthanon National Park in
Chiang Mai, northern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The fires have destroyed more than 17,000 rai (2,720 hectares)
of forest since March 20, according to the Nation newspaper on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Anuisidh Methawalalak, the park's chief, as
saying that small fires could continue for another two months but
firefighters could manage to handle the situation, with the
support of various agencies and volunteers.
</P>
<P>
"It is the first time that such serious fires have broken out
in the virgin forest at such a great altitude, where it is
normally saturated with moisture," Anuisidh said.
</P>
<P>
He said the fire-raged areas could partly recover naturally,
though some of the areas could take as long as 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Agriculture Minister Newin Chidchob, who directed the
fire control, said he had formed another 15 fire-monitoring units
in the park to help the 14 fire-control units already in
operation.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that hill-tribe people and members of the Northern
Farmers' Network (NFN) had deliberately set the fires in a bid to
expand their farmland.
</P>
<P>
But an NFN spokesman denied the charge, saying the fires were a
natural disaster partly caused by El-Nino.
</P>
<P>
Several fires have been reported in other parts of the country
and have destroyed large areas of forests. Some of the fires were
still raging. 
</P>
</TEXT>
