<HEADLINE> German Women Dominate Speed Skating Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Germany's women skaters repeated
their sweep of medals on the last day of the World Speed Skating
Single Distance Champoinships in Calgary on Sunday, this time in
the 1,500 meters event.
</P>
<P>
German skater Anni Friesinger cruised to the gold from the
1,500 meters event in one minute 56. 95 seconds, breaking the
world record of 1:57.58, which was set by Dutch skater Marianne
Timmer at Nagano, Japan, in February.
</P>
<P>
Timmer, the defending world champion from the Netherlands, was
forced out after falling onto the ice while entering a corner.
</P>
<P>
Another German Gunda Niemann, gold medalist in women's 3,000
meters, took the silver in 1:57.20, lagging behind her compatriot
by only 0.25 second. Her compatriot Claudia Pechstein got the
bronze in 1:57.30.
</P>
<P>
Sunday was the second time that the three German ladies shone
at the worlds. They swept through the 3,000 meters on the first
day of the championships, with Niemann taking the gold, Pechstein
the silver and Friesinger the bronze.
</P>
<P>
While the three German speed skaters excelled in women's events,
the Dutches did an excellent job in men's 10,000 as well as 5,000
meters events.
</P>
<P>
Following Friday's gold and silver in men's 5,000 meters, the
Dutch demonstrated once again Sunday their strengths in men's
10,000 meters event.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic gold medalist Gianni Romme broke his own world
record of the 10,000 meters by 6.62 seconds, clocking 13:08.71.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, his compatriot Bob de Jong took the silver in
13:22.64, while Germany's Frank Dittrich got the bronze.
</P>
<P>
The men's 1,000 meters seemed to be Canada's specialty.
Sylvain Bouchard sprinted to gold in 1:09.60, with 0.56 second
faster than the world record, which was set by his countryman
Jeremy Wotherspoon in the same Olympic Oval last year.
</P>
<P>
Wotherspoon lost his title by 0.07 second. He got the silver
while Japanese skater Hiroyasu Shimizu took the bronze.
</P>
<P>
The three-day world championships ended on Sunday, with Germany
being the single biggest winner of medals here, raking in one
third of the 30 medals.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands and Canada ranked second, with each getting six
medals. They were followed by Japan, which won three medals,
including one gold.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Norway each took home one gold. Russia
won a silver, while Italy and Belgium got a bronze respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
