<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Reform Commercial Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will introduce
comprehensive commercial law reforms aimed at boosting private
sector investment, the official Daily News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Finance G. L. Peiris told the paper that the
project will be funded by the World Bank and that technical
support will be provided by the Law and Society Trust.
</P>
<P>
Peiris was quoted as saying that a major constraint had been
the delay in handling commercial law-related disputes.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed at providing material and legal
infrastructure to support the growth of entrepreneurship and
commercial activity.
</P>
<P>
It will provide advanced methods of data retrieval and will
provide access to international commercial law sources via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
Another priority area will be the training of members of the
judiciary particularly in commercial law and related fields whilst
upgrading of the facilities available for judicial training will
also be undertaken.  
</P>
