<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft to Launch Windows 98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft plans the worldwide
release of Windows 98, a new generation of its operating system,
in the second quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
In a recent visit to China Pieter Knook, vice president of
Microsoft's Far East Region, also revealed that the Chinese
version of Windows 98 is scheduled for release in the fall.
</P>
<P>
The delay in introducing Chinese versions of relevant
English-based software products has been reduced from the previous
two months to less than 40 days, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Actually, last September we simultaneously launched both the
English and Chinese versions of Internet Explorer 4.0. in Los
Angeles and Beijing," Knook said.
</P>
<P>
In a preview held here Friday, technicians for the
U.S. software giant said the new product is mainly directed at
family users, as well as medium- or small-sized enterprises. The
new products, based on Windows 95 which was introduced three years
ago, can run faster and is more stable with a more powerful
systems management.
</P>
<P>
The '98 version has a seamless connection with the Internet,
which enables users to quickly surf the Net on the same interface.
</P>
<P>
The company has already distributed Beta testing copies for
professional users.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese is now one of the five major languages used by
Microsoft-developed software products," said Jia-Bin Duh,
president of Microsoft (China), adding that this indicates the
importance of the China market to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show China's software sales last year were
11.2 billion yuan, up 20.1 percent over 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
