<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Friesinger Sets Speedskating World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Anni Friesinger set a
world record in the women's 1,500 meters, becoming the first women
to smash the one minute 57 second barrier at the Speedskating
World Championships in Calgary, Canada, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Friesinger, who finished fifth in the same event at the Nagano
Olympics, clocked in 1:56.93, eclipising the old mark of 1:57.58
set by Marianne Timmer of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
"My biggest problem is my starts so I knew I had to open fast
and I did," said Friesinger, a soldier in the German army. "To win
I knew it would take a world record but I didn't expect it would
be me."
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old, who started speed skating at the age of nine,
bettered her personal best by over two seconds.
</P>
<P>
Gianni Romme of the Netherlands rewrote his own world record in
13:08.71 in the men's 10,000m, over 6 seconds faster than his old
mark of 13:15.33.
</P>
<P>
Romme also set a world record in the men's 5,000m on the
opening day.
</P>
<P>
Japanese speedster Hiroyasu Shimizu also set three records in
two events over the final two days. After his double world records
Saturday, he clocked 1:09.83 in the men's 1,000m on Sunday. His
mark was just 10 minutes fresh before it was broken by Canada's
Sylvain Bouchard with a 1:09.60.
</P>
<P>
Bouchard finished his career on high note, winning the men's
1,000m in a record time of 1:09.60, while runner-up and teammate
Jeremy Wotherspoon was also under previous world record time with
a 1:09.67.
</P>
<P>
Nine of 10 events' world records were broken in Calgary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian Air Force Plane Crash Kills 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 29 (Xinhua) -- At least twenty-eight people were
killed Sunday when a Peruvian Air Force cargo plane carrying more
than 50 people crashed in a shantytown in northern Peru, President
Alberto Fujimori said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty more passengers were injured in the crash, and 15 people
survived after the plane plunged into a canal and split in two,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The air force pilot, whose plane suffered engine problems,
narrowly avoided an otherwise much worse disaster by guiding the
aircraft over dozens of homes to crash-land in an irrigation
channel that ran through the center of the shantytown, Fujimori
said.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori, who was informed of the crash while on a visit to the
city of Trujillo, said he was told the pilot was unable to avert
the crash but was able to steer away from the inhabited areas by
operating the craft as a glider.
</P>
<P>
The plane was ferrying civilians between towns in northern Peru
because violent El Nino-driven storms had triggered floods and
mudslides, blocking some land routes.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori, who spoke in the nearby town of Trujillo, said some
surviving passengers were able to walk away from the crash
site. The plane's five-member crew survived the crash.
</P>
<P>
Teams of rescuers dragged bodies from the fuselage and
transported those injured in the crash to Piura's city hospital.
They also began to haul the plane's wreckage from the canal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
