<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Holds Parliamentary Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine held its Supreme Soviet
(parliament) and local elections Sunday, with some 65 percent of
the 37 million eligible people participating in the voting.
</P>
<P>
The country's central election committee said that 6,452
candidates joined the competition to run for the 450 seats of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time for Ukrainians to vote for
parliamentary representatives since the country declared
independence in 1991. The last elections were held four years ago.
</P>
<P>
President Leonid Kuchma told reporters after casting his vote
that the primary task for the new parliament is to adopt a set of
economic laws.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko said that his government is
ready to have an effective cooperation with the parliament.
</P>
<P>
According to Ukraine's constitution, half the 450 seats will
proportionally go to the parties which gain at least 4 percent of
the votes, and the other 225 representatives will be elected
directly in the 225 constituencies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the local elections were also held Sunday throughout
the country, except in the capital city of Kiev and Sevastopol, a
port city in Crimea peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
