<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Lending Mostly Confines to Human Development, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 29 (Xinhua) -- President of the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) Mitsuo Sato said Sunday that ADB's lending
to Pakistan will mostly confine to human development and poverty
alleviation in the future.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here at the end of his three-day
visit to Pakistan, Sato said that the Bank will extend all
possible cooperation and assistance to help Pakistan achieve
sustained economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"The Bank will continue the way it can to help Pakistan in
social sector, particularly to alleviate poverty," said the ADB
president.
</P>
<P>
According to Sato, the lending program agreed with the
Pakistani government this month comprises five loans for a total
of 677 million U.S. dollars, of which 112 million dollars are from
the Asian Development Fund and 565 million dollars from ADB's
Ordinary Capital Resources.
</P>
<P>
He said that human development, with particular focus on gender
needs, remains the foremost priority of the Bank strategy for
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"This will be addressed through assistance to education,
health, population, and urban development," Sato added.
</P>
<P>
It is the policy of the Bank to provide assistance to those
countries which are making efforts to transform their economies
and Pakistan qualifies for that, he said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz said on the occasion that ADB has
become the largest donor for Pakistan as the recent tranche of 600
million dollars is the biggest ever donation for one year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
