<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Envoy Meets Afghan Representatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PESHAWAR, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Special Envoy of the
U.N. Secretary General Lakhar Brahimi and Ambassador of the
Organization of Islamic Conference Mukhtar Lamani held talks
Sunday with representatives of various Afghan factions.
</P>
<P>
In Peshawar, capital of Pakistan's North West Frontier Province
(NWFP), Brahimi and Lamani discussed different proposals with the
Afghan representatives in a bid to solve the long-running Afghan
issue.
</P>
<P>
However, details about the meetings were not immediately
available.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, Brahimi called on NWFP Chief Secretary Rustam
Shah in Peshawar.
</P>
<P>
He discussed with Shah matters relating to peace in war-torn
Afghanistan and U.N. efforts in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. special envoy arrived in Islamabad on March 20 on his
fresh peace mission to the region.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Islamabad, Brahimi held talks with the
Pakistani leaders, including President Rafiq Tarar and Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif. He also held talks with Mollah M. Rabbani,
the second most senior leader of the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi is expected to visit Afghanistan and other countries in
the region as part of his three-week peace mission. 
</P>
