<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rios Wins Lipton Tennis to Claim No. 1 Ranking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Chilean Marcelo Rios had the
greatest day of his life on Sunday when he beat Andre Agassi in
the Lipton tennis finals to claim the No. 1 spot in the world.
</P>
<P>
Rios had his near-flawless performance to outpower Agassi 7-5,
6-3, 6-4 as the Chilean and American fans traded chants in Key
Biscayne, Florida.
</P>
<P>
Currently ranked third, Rios will end Sampras' streak of 102
consecutive weeks atop the rankings on Monday, and become the
first South American to be No. 1 since the ATP rankings began in
1973.
</P>
<P>
Sampras was upset in the third round by Wayne Ferreira.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, Rios was the second player to be ranked first
without winning a Grand Slam. The other was Ivan Lendl in 1983,
who went on to win eight majors.
</P>
<P>
The Lipton title was the most prestigious for Rios which
awarded him the first prize of 360,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
As hundreds of Chilean fans flocked to Florida, Rios had an
early lead of 3-0 before Agassi pulled back at 5-5 in the first
set.
</P>
<P>
As Agassi committed double faults, Rios fixed his eyes to taste
the No.1 spotting by winning a stretch of seven games later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980330.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hickman Enjoys Limelight in Paris World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 29 (Xinhua) -- James Hickman of Britain became the
most impressive swimmer in the World Cup short-course swimming by
taking four titles with one world record here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old broke the world record and snatched the gold in
the 200 meters butterfly.
</P>
<P>
Apart from his victory in the 100m medley, Hickman carried on
his winning streak in the 100m butterfly for a European record of
51.46 seconds, and a Commonwealth record of 1:55.80 in the 200m
medley.
</P>
<P>
Australian Micheal Klim chased Hickman all the way on the
second length but couldn't quite claw the gap, finishing in 52.04,
almost a second off his own world record in the event.
</P>
<P>
Russian legend Alexander Popov, who was beaten in the 100m
freestyle on Saturday, suffered another disappointment as he was
disqualified in the 50m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Italian Lorenzo Vismara, who beat Popov last Wednesday in
Imperia, Italy, took the title in 21.94 seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
